WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.400
[Amit Varma]: We live in a time of great human tragedy. You might well ask why discuss economics then?

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:19.240
[Amit Varma]: I will give you three reasons. One, every human tragedy reflects itself in data somewhere.

00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Numbers might seem inert and lifeless, but if one knows how to parse numbers and add

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:29.920
[Amit Varma]: context to them, those numbers can throb with life. We can discern stories that might otherwise

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:37.420
[Amit Varma]: be unseen by us. Two, economics has consequences. It affects the lives of common people. Bad

00:00:37.420 --> 00:00:44.320
[Amit Varma]: economic policy like much of what Indira Gandhi did in the 1970s or Narendra Modi's demonetization

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:51.320
[Amit Varma]: causes real human suffering. Understanding economics helps us understand the causes of

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:58.360
[Amit Varma]: suffering and might help us prevent or lessen it in whatever capacity we can. And three,

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:03.600
[Amit Varma]: economics is the study of human behavior. To understand the incentives that drive us,

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:09.040
[Amit Varma]: the trade-offs we face and the choices we make, we must understand economics. For this

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:19.800
[Amit Varma]: reason, perhaps in this time of great suffering, understanding economics is important.

00:01:19.800 --> 00:01:25.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:31.480
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bhadwa.

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:36.400
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen. Today's episode is about the Indian economy in the

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:42.560
[Amit Varma]: time of COVID-19. My guest is Vivek Kaul with whom I had done an episode in December, summing

00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:47.400
[Amit Varma]: up the year gone by. We thought things were looking bad, but boy, what I would give to

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:53.200
[Amit Varma]: be in December again. COVID-19 has ravaged economies throughout the world and has caused

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:58.800
[Amit Varma]: pain and misery on an unimaginable scale. This pain is not just across space all over

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:05.800
[Amit Varma]: the world, but also across time, for the repercussions of this crisis will be felt by us way into

00:02:05.800 --> 00:02:11.480
[Amit Varma]: the future, perhaps even by future generations. In all this gloom, I also want to mention

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:17.320
[Amit Varma]: a couple of things that you can look forward to. One, Vivek's new book, Bad Money, is out

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:25.600
[Amit Varma]: now. It deals with the NPMS and takes a closer look at India's banking system. And two, Vivek

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:31.160
[Amit Varma]: and I are starting a new weekly podcast called Econ Central, in which we will chat about

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:37.040
[Amit Varma]: the events of the week, demystifying economics, and looking at other news through the lens

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:42.600
[Amit Varma]: of economic thinking. That launches later this week, and Vivek and I will tell you about

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:52.160
[Amit Varma]: it as this conversation begins. But first, a quick commercial break.

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:57.360
[Amit Varma]: In the last few months, I have spent hundreds, if not thousands of hours watching TikTok.

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:03.080
[Amit Varma]: You might consider it an addiction. And indeed, TikTok always gets my dopamine going. I don't

00:03:03.080 --> 00:03:09.080
[Amit Varma]: call this addiction though. I call it sociological research, or even taking one for the team.

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:14.960
[Amit Varma]: I have designed a new course called TikTok and Indian Society, and I invite you to be

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:21.080
[Amit Varma]: part of it. I believe that TikTok reflects real India better than any other outlet for

00:03:21.080 --> 00:03:26.360
[Amit Varma]: news and entertainment. Our mainstream sources of news and entertainment are controlled by

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:33.160
[Amit Varma]: elites who just don't get small town India, or village India, or poor India, or even young

00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:38.460
[Amit Varma]: aspirational India. Because TikTok has blown away these barriers, and given the means of

00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:44.820
[Amit Varma]: production to everyone, it has empowered people who otherwise did not have a voice or a platform.

00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:49.880
[Amit Varma]: And I'm blown away by the talent I see every day on this app. And my eyes are also opened

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:55.960
[Amit Varma]: to so many shades and nuances of India that I had not noticed before. We see the worst

00:03:55.960 --> 00:04:01.760
[Amit Varma]: of India in our prejudices and attitudes, but also the best in our creativity and our

00:04:01.760 --> 00:04:07.360
[Amit Varma]: descent. My course is unique, as it will be conducted, surprise, surprise, on WhatsApp,

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:13.420
[Amit Varma]: and will involve both my thoughts on the many teams I discuss, as well as hundreds of amazing

00:04:13.420 --> 00:04:20.400
[Amit Varma]: videos that illustrate my points. I am charging rupees 5000 for this course, to head on over

00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:28.440
[Amit Varma]: to cnunseen.in slash TikTok to enroll for TikTok and Indian Society. My new course over

00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:38.840
[Amit Varma]: at cnunseen.in slash TikTok. Vivek, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:04:38.840 --> 00:04:43.360
[Guest]: Thanks, Amit for having me over. And, you know, what is this new course you are planning

00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:48.120
[Amit Varma]: on TikTok of all the things? Yeah, as you know, I've spent hundreds and thousands of

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:54.240
[Amit Varma]: hours watching TikTok over the last few months, and I call it research, not timepass. And

00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:58.040
[Amit Varma]: one of the, you know, things I've realized while watching TikTok is that, you know, it's

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:04.480
[Amit Varma]: really democratized the creation of entertainment in India, most of the other entertainment

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:09.280
[Amit Varma]: that we see around us is controlled by elites, like, you know, Bollywood is controlled by

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:13.920
[Amit Varma]: elites who are disconnected from a lot of reality, and so on. But TikTok really has

00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:19.240
[Amit Varma]: gone into small towns and villages all over the country. And, you know, made it easy for

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:23.960
[Amit Varma]: people to make videos and made the means of production available to all. And what that

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:29.160
[Amit Varma]: has done is that has shown us a side of India, which many of us English speaking elites never

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:33.800
[Amit Varma]: see. And I found that fascinating. And I started taking notes on it. And I realized that both

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:39.840
[Amit Varma]: the worst and the best of India can be reflected in the glimpses of culture that we see through

00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:45.680
[Amit Varma]: TikTok. And of course, all the worst of it is there like the misogyny and the normalization

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:51.120
[Amit Varma]: of casual violence, and all of that. But you also see a lot of other things, the, you know,

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:56.560
[Amit Varma]: more women expressing themselves and expressing their sexuality, much more political dissent

00:05:56.560 --> 00:06:01.760
[Amit Varma]: in very subtle ways. There's great satire, great irony. So I thought I should sort of

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:07.560
[Amit Varma]: make a structured course where I talk about all the themes that I have noticed about it.

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:14.400
[Guest]: So you know, what you're basically saying is, TikTok has done to content what social

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:19.840
[Guest]: media in a way did to news, you know, the tyranny of the editor, as in as we used to

00:06:19.840 --> 00:06:26.400
[Guest]: say, only what the editor decided ultimately appeared in a newspaper or even on a website.

00:06:26.400 --> 00:06:30.520
[Guest]: But you know, with social media and with people, you know, having a mobile phone and a camera

00:06:30.520 --> 00:06:35.680
[Guest]: in their hands, the tyranny of the editor is dead. So you know, so basically, you know,

00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:37.680
[Amit Varma]: TikTok is another version of that.

00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:42.880
[Amit Varma]: TikTok is another version of that. But it's beautiful that because even when so you know,

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:46.800
[Amit Varma]: the internet killed the tyranny of the editor, social media killed that it was still only

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:51.480
[Amit Varma]: available to people with an internet connection and by and large people who could speak and

00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:55.440
[Amit Varma]: communicate in English. And I think TikTok is completely broken that I mean, I see so

00:06:55.440 --> 00:07:01.600
[Amit Varma]: many great videos from small villages and so on, and incredible sophistication, even

00:07:01.600 --> 00:07:06.560
[Amit Varma]: in the filmmaking. So within the bounds of what you can do the 15 second videos, a cheap

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:11.600
[Amit Varma]: mobile phone cameras, they're producing incredible stuff, which reveals so much.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:18.600
[Guest]: Indeed, I mean, I'm also on TikTok, though not as much as you are. And sometimes it's

00:07:18.600 --> 00:07:23.560
[Guest]: actually a real pleasure. Because you know, you do end up laughing at the content that

00:07:23.560 --> 00:07:28.640
[Guest]: they create. So I think we're planning to use WhatsApp to sort of deliver this course.

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:29.640
[Amit Varma]: What's the idea there?

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:35.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so you know, Vivek, you and I joke so often on this show about WhatsApp University.

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:39.040
[Amit Varma]: And this is probably the first time somebody is using WhatsApp for a course like this in

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:43.840
[Amit Varma]: all seriousness. And the reason for that is I'll actually be sharing hundreds of videos

00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:48.200
[Amit Varma]: through the course as illustration of the themes that I mean, so that people sort of

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:53.040
[Amit Varma]: kind of understand that and these are all you know, as in TikTok vertical format videos.

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:56.320
[Amit Varma]: And so you can't do a zoom class with them where you show hundreds of these vertical

00:07:56.320 --> 00:08:01.240
[Amit Varma]: videos, there's really no other, you can't create YouTube modules, the only way to really

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:05.800
[Amit Varma]: do the I mean, WhatsApp is perfect for this, because it's meant for forwarding videos and

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:12.080
[Amit Varma]: all of that. And my course will really happen through a WhatsApp group, which is where only

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:17.560
[Amit Varma]: the admin can post. So it's only me and I'll kind of run the course on that. And that should

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:21.920
[Amit Varma]: be great fun. But moving on from that, and thank you for asking me about this and giving

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:27.040
[Amit Varma]: me this extra publicity. I hope listeners check that out at cnunseen.in slash TikTok.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:31.800
[Amit Varma]: But what you and I are as excited about, if not more, in fact, we've been talking about

00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:39.160
[Amit Varma]: it for more than a year, bro, is our own co-hosted show, Econ Central. It's a weekly half an

00:08:39.160 --> 00:08:42.840
[Amit Varma]: hour podcast. And Vivek, just tell our listeners a little bit more about that.

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:48.160
[Guest]: Okay, Amit, as we've been discussing, and as we've been talking for a while, the idea

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:57.520
[Guest]: here is to sort of lay out economics, which matters to the common man in a lucid, very

00:08:57.520 --> 00:09:05.320
[Guest]: simple sort of way. And there are two sort of, you know, facets to it. One is the fact

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:10.240
[Guest]: that what has happened over the years is as the tyranny of the editor has died, a lot

00:09:10.240 --> 00:09:16.800
[Guest]: of false news, you know, goes around. And economics also sort of gets included into

00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:21.960
[Guest]: it. And it becomes very difficult for people to sort of figure out as to what is right

00:09:21.960 --> 00:09:28.840
[Guest]: and what is wrong. So in that sense, the idea behind the show is to take, you know, a particular

00:09:28.840 --> 00:09:35.480
[Guest]: topic which is in the news at that point of time, and explain it in a very simple, lucid

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:41.480
[Guest]: sort of way. The other thing that happens is the fact that, you know, the conventional

00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:49.560
[Guest]: mainstream media, be it TV channels, be it digital publications or newspapers, approach

00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:55.600
[Guest]: economics in a very complex, expert-driven sort of a way. You know, it's like everyone's

00:09:55.600 --> 00:10:01.560
[Guest]: talking in code. And unless you understand the language of that code, you know, you don't

00:10:01.560 --> 00:10:09.160
[Guest]: understand what is, you know, being communicated. So the idea is to break that again and talk

00:10:09.160 --> 00:10:16.080
[Guest]: economics in simple English and explain to people as to how one, you know, why they should

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:22.040
[Guest]: be bothered about it, you know, as citizens of this nation, and two, how it impacts their

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:26.680
[Guest]: daily lives. You know, we don't really, most of the times, we don't realize that a lot

00:10:26.680 --> 00:10:32.520
[Guest]: of what is happening in the Indian economy, and even in the global economy for that matter,

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:37.480
[Guest]: impacts our lives in very, very different ways. And we don't even realize it. So forget

00:10:37.480 --> 00:10:42.680
[Guest]: sort of preparing for it. We don't even know that it is happening to us. So I think that

00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:49.040
[Guest]: is the basic idea behind the show, so that people who have no background, or I'll put

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:55.120
[Guest]: it this way, people who have no degree in economics can log in and understand what's

00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:56.120
[Guest]: what's going on.

00:10:56.120 --> 00:11:01.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And what also fascinated me about the show is that when, you know, when people talk

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:05.360
[Amit Varma]: about economics, partly because of the reason you mentioned that mainstream publications

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:10.040
[Amit Varma]: use so much jargon, and they almost restrict it to specialists, partly because of that,

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:14.320
[Amit Varma]: but people think of something of economics as something arcane that doesn't apply to

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:19.600
[Amit Varma]: the world outside of money. And that's always been something that's irritated me because

00:11:19.600 --> 00:11:24.600
[Amit Varma]: I look at economics as the study of human behavior. And I think it applies to everything

00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:29.720
[Amit Varma]: the tools of economics, looking at incentives, understanding trade offs apply to every facet

00:11:29.720 --> 00:11:35.680
[Amit Varma]: of our lives. So what we will also do through our new podcast, Econ Central is, you know,

00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:41.760
[Amit Varma]: talk about regular news in India, whether it's in politics or in entertainment, or wherever,

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:46.680
[Amit Varma]: look at regular news through the prism of economic thinking, you know, before we begin

00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:50.780
[Amit Varma]: this particular show, just some information for the listener. Typically, when you launch

00:11:50.780 --> 00:11:55.440
[Amit Varma]: a podcast, you first put a preview podcast out there. So that, you know, broadcast apps

00:11:55.440 --> 00:12:01.760
[Amit Varma]: can pick up the RSS feed and like a week after that, you actually put up Episode One, Episode

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:06.320
[Amit Varma]: One will come later this week on Thursday, probably we haven't decided which day of the

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:12.160
[Amit Varma]: week to release it. But the preview episode is already out, the RSS feed has been submitted

00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:19.080
[Amit Varma]: to all podcast apps. So do go over to whatever podcast app you use, and look for Econ Central,

00:12:19.080 --> 00:12:26.240
[Amit Varma]: Econ Central. And you can also go to econcentral.in. Though that is under construction right now,

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:30.120
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if it will be ready at the time of the seen unseen episode, but it will be

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:34.160
[Amit Varma]: ready when the first episode of Econ Central is actually out. So you can follow that for

00:12:34.160 --> 00:12:40.240
[Amit Varma]: updates. And in any case, we'll be mentioning that on Twitter. Now having got all the publicity

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:44.040
[Amit Varma]: of the various things we are doing out of the way, you know, before we start talking

00:12:44.040 --> 00:12:47.520
[Amit Varma]: about you know, the Indian economy during COVID, which is, you know, what the theme

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:51.200
[Amit Varma]: of the show is, tell me a little bit about how you've been managing during the lockdown.

00:12:51.200 --> 00:12:52.680
[Guest]: What's life been like for you?

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:58.960
[Guest]: Actually, this is a question I get asked often these days. And very honestly, my life hasn't

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:03.920
[Guest]: changed at all, because this is the life I normally lead. Wherein, you know, I work out

00:13:03.920 --> 00:13:09.480
[Guest]: of home, I get up in the morning, I make my breakfast, I write my stuff, I take my nap

00:13:09.480 --> 00:13:16.120
[Guest]: in the afternoon, and then I read in the evenings. And obviously, then, you know, at around 8,

00:13:16.120 --> 00:13:22.440
[Guest]: 8.30pm, I cook. So that is pretty much what has been happening. The only difference that

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:27.160
[Guest]: has come in is that obviously, you know, I would probably go out a couple of times a

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:34.360
[Guest]: week and socialize. So that has, you know, that is not happening. And most of the stuff

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:40.840
[Guest]: is being home delivered. So other than that, my life is pretty much like the way it used

00:13:40.840 --> 00:13:47.240
[Guest]: to be. Now, the interesting thing is what a lot of my friends who have worked out of

00:13:47.240 --> 00:13:52.880
[Guest]: home in the last three months, have realized is that working out of home is not easy. Because

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:58.320
[Guest]: one, there is no one sitting on your head to sort of do the work that you have to. And

00:13:58.320 --> 00:14:05.200
[Guest]: two, it is very difficult to get into a routine, at least for them, because for them, you know,

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:10.920
[Guest]: you go to office, and then you sort of have your cup of coffee, you gossip a little and

00:14:10.920 --> 00:14:15.280
[Guest]: then your computer warms up in the meanwhile, and then work starts. So all these little

00:14:15.280 --> 00:14:22.800
[Guest]: things have gone out of the window. And obviously, for a lot of men who have been brought up

00:14:22.800 --> 00:14:27.680
[Guest]: by their mothers not so well, you know, it's been a real challenge because when your home

00:14:27.680 --> 00:14:33.280
[Guest]: help is not coming, and your wife cannot possibly be doing all the things. So for them, it's

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:37.960
[Guest]: just you know, a lot of them have washed utensils in their lives for the first time, some of

00:14:37.960 --> 00:14:42.000
[Guest]: them have discovered cooking. I mean, like a friend was telling me the other day, I didn't

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:48.880
[Guest]: know paneer banana itna aasan tha. So yeah, so that's the but yeah, I mean, so the interesting

00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:53.360
[Amit Varma]: thing is a lot of people have realized that working out of home is not easy.

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:57.360
[Amit Varma]: And maybe a lot of men appreciate their wives a little bit more all the unpaid labor that

00:14:57.360 --> 00:15:02.760
[Guest]: they took for granted. I mean, you know, hats off to all the working women who used to sort

00:15:02.760 --> 00:15:08.600
[Guest]: of manage their homes as well. I mean, so all the men are now gradually sort of, I mean,

00:15:08.600 --> 00:15:12.760
[Guest]: I don't think it's going to make a big change. But yes, a few people here and there have

00:15:12.760 --> 00:15:20.160
[Amit Varma]: realized that it's very difficult. Yeah, among the many sort of interesting, unseen consequences

00:15:20.160 --> 00:15:23.880
[Amit Varma]: of the lockdown could be how relationships between the sexes change in many different

00:15:23.880 --> 00:15:27.680
[Amit Varma]: ways, good ways, bad ways. And obviously, I share a sentiment because I've kind of been

00:15:27.680 --> 00:15:32.600
[Amit Varma]: working from home for the last 13 or 14 years. And for me, this is like, not the new normal,

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:36.200
[Amit Varma]: it's the old normal, everyone else is sharing in it and cribbing about it. And I'm like,

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:40.480
[Amit Varma]: what are you even talking about? And I completely agree with you about the difficulty of self

00:15:40.480 --> 00:15:43.880
[Amit Varma]: discipline, though, you are obviously far better at it than I am, because you churn

00:15:43.880 --> 00:15:49.160
[Amit Varma]: out 83 articles every week. And you know, I struggle with whatever little I have to

00:15:49.160 --> 00:15:54.400
[Amit Varma]: do. So you know, let's get to the subject of the show before our listeners throw their

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:58.120
[Amit Varma]: smartphones where they are listening to this into the sink because they're presumably washing

00:15:58.120 --> 00:16:01.680
[Amit Varma]: dishes while listening to us, which is the most common use case. That's when I listen

00:16:01.680 --> 00:16:08.320
[Guest]: to podcasts, by the way, very little walking and running that's been happening. So I'm

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:13.280
[Guest]: traveling. Yeah, you can't be you know, you are not spending two hours in your car and

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:18.720
[Amit Varma]: sort of listening to a podcast. So yeah, so we you know, the two of us did an episode

00:16:18.720 --> 00:16:22.080
[Amit Varma]: of the seen and the unseen in at the end of December, which I linked from the show notes

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:27.280
[Amit Varma]: where we spoke about the economy in 2019. And, you know, we have done various episodes

00:16:27.280 --> 00:16:32.560
[Amit Varma]: on aspects of the economy in the last three years. We've covered, you know, events like

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:38.440
[Amit Varma]: demonetization and GST and pakora nomics, a term coined by Vivek Kaul, everyone multiple

00:16:38.440 --> 00:16:43.480
[Amit Varma]: times. And in our episode, the economy in 2019, while summing up what happened that

00:16:43.480 --> 00:16:49.320
[Amit Varma]: year in terms of economic news, we also laid out a pretty bleak picture of the government's

00:16:49.320 --> 00:16:54.160
[Amit Varma]: management of the economy, things have been going downhill for a long time. And the COVID

00:16:54.160 --> 00:17:00.120
[Amit Varma]: lockdown, of course, started at the end of March. Can you sort of give me a snapshot

00:17:00.120 --> 00:17:06.200
[Amit Varma]: of in your view, how the Indian economy stood on the eve of the lockdown? Like, you know,

00:17:06.200 --> 00:17:10.080
[Amit Varma]: how bad were things were some things improving? Were they getting worse? Were we drifting?

00:17:10.080 --> 00:17:14.960
[Amit Varma]: We've had many crisis which are getting worse, like credit crisis, jobs crisis, etc. Where

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:19.720
[Guest]: did we stand? Okay, so you know, as I have, you know, been writing in the last three months,

00:17:19.720 --> 00:17:26.120
[Guest]: I think we were already pretty much into an economic slowdown by the time the COVID-19,

00:17:26.120 --> 00:17:32.280
[Guest]: you know, came around. So I remember, you know, one of the pieces that I wrote for Mint

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:38.360
[Guest]: was headlined something like the psychology of a slowdown. And this was late last year.

00:17:38.360 --> 00:17:43.880
[Guest]: So I think by the end of December, and you know, when we did our year end episode, there

00:17:43.880 --> 00:17:49.520
[Guest]: were many economic indicators, which clearly showed that the economy was not doing well.

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:56.200
[Guest]: I mean, you could look at stuff, you know, everything from car sales to two wheeler sales,

00:17:56.200 --> 00:18:01.080
[Guest]: to investment happening in the economy, credit growth, multiple indicators, which would have

00:18:01.080 --> 00:18:07.200
[Guest]: told you that the economy is not doing so well. And in fact, recently, the GDP numbers

00:18:07.200 --> 00:18:16.160
[Guest]: for 2019-20 were released. And the funny thing is that the economy grew by 4.2% during the

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:22.120
[Guest]: course of the year, which was very slow. But if you take out the government's contribution

00:18:22.120 --> 00:18:28.560
[Guest]: out of it, the economy grew at just around 3.3%. Now, what has been happening in the

00:18:28.560 --> 00:18:35.480
[Guest]: last three years is that the government expenditure has been growing at a very fast pace. And

00:18:35.480 --> 00:18:41.120
[Guest]: that has essentially been lifting up the overall economy. But this is not something, you know,

00:18:41.120 --> 00:18:46.720
[Guest]: which can one, continue forever, and two, it cannot lift the economy beyond a point

00:18:46.720 --> 00:18:52.760
[Guest]: because the government does not form a very large part of the Indian economy. Let me put

00:18:52.760 --> 00:18:59.400
[Guest]: it this way, when politicians started recognizing COVID-19 as a serious issue, which was probably

00:18:59.400 --> 00:19:07.600
[Guest]: first to second week of March, the Indian economy was already in deep trouble by then.

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:12.080
[Guest]: And since then, we have only gone downhill like has the rest of the world.

00:19:12.080 --> 00:19:16.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And in fact, you know, just to drive home the point that you're making in our last

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:22.440
[Amit Varma]: episode, we spoke about what is my pet bugbear really about the measurement of the GDP. And

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:27.040
[Amit Varma]: this was a debate that happened in the late 1930s. And Simon Kuznets, who is known as

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:32.440
[Amit Varma]: a father of the GDP, said that government spending should not be included in GDP, because

00:19:32.440 --> 00:19:37.400
[Amit Varma]: then what can happen is it becomes easy. If you're using GDP as a measure of growth, it

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:42.400
[Amit Varma]: becomes easy for the government to game that measure. You can just dig 1000 ditches, pay

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:47.040
[Amit Varma]: people to dig 1000 ditches, fill them up, dig them again, fill them up again. And without

00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:52.000
[Amit Varma]: anything productive being done, the GDP just keeps going up. And then you can point to

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:57.080
[Amit Varma]: those figures and see how well they are doing. But there is a limit to how much you can game

00:19:57.080 --> 00:20:00.400
[Amit Varma]: them because first of all, where does the money that the government is spending come

00:20:00.400 --> 00:20:05.400
[Amit Varma]: from? It comes from the people, there is an opportunity cost to it. In a great episode

00:20:05.400 --> 00:20:11.000
[Amit Varma]: I did with Ajay Shah and Vijay Kelkar earlier this year, a few months ago, they pointed

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:16.360
[Amit Varma]: out that they pointed out something called the marginal cost of government funds, government

00:20:16.360 --> 00:20:20.920
[Amit Varma]: spending, which basically means that for every one rupee that the government spends, the

00:20:20.920 --> 00:20:26.520
[Amit Varma]: cost to GDP growth is equal to that of three rupees approximately in India is between two

00:20:26.520 --> 00:20:30.660
[Amit Varma]: and a half to three and a half, but you can approximate it to that. So the cost of every

00:20:30.660 --> 00:20:35.640
[Amit Varma]: one rupee spent by the government is three rupees in the overall sense, that's the opportunity

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:41.120
[Amit Varma]: cost. So that's, again, something that you have to consider. So even if this metric is

00:20:41.120 --> 00:20:45.640
[Amit Varma]: inaccurate and has been gamed in this way, that really can't continue. And we were in

00:20:45.640 --> 00:20:50.000
[Amit Varma]: bad shape anyway. I mean, after all these years of talking of 8% growth, four and a

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:54.320
[Amit Varma]: half percent, even with government spending, you know, being spoken of as part of GDP is

00:20:54.320 --> 00:20:58.400
[Amit Varma]: pretty miserable things have gone wrong. I'd also recommend listeners listen to an episode

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:03.640
[Amit Varma]: a link from the show notes, which I did with Pooja Mehra about the last decade where she

00:21:03.640 --> 00:21:10.120
[Amit Varma]: lays out that all of this really started in 2011. And we've had a decade of disastrous

00:21:10.120 --> 00:21:17.000
[Amit Varma]: economic management since. And so my question to you here is this, and I don't want to belabor

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:22.000
[Amit Varma]: the point of data and what metrics we look at to judge how the economy is doing. But

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:26.640
[Amit Varma]: in the context of COVID, it becomes acute because in many earlier episodes, we've lamented

00:21:26.640 --> 00:21:31.800
[Amit Varma]: how, you know, data is so unreliable. And what are the different kinds of proxies and

00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:36.360
[Amit Varma]: metrics by which we can talk about the economy. In the time of COVID, it seems to me that

00:21:36.360 --> 00:21:41.120
[Amit Varma]: that has been exacerbated, like early on in the lockdown, you wrote a piece about how

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:47.380
[Amit Varma]: real freight prices were indicating what's going on. So when someone who covers economics

00:21:47.380 --> 00:21:52.320
[Amit Varma]: and looks at it as closely as you looks at what is happening after COVID, besides, of

00:21:52.320 --> 00:21:56.840
[Amit Varma]: course, the anecdotal evidence all around us, which are mostly stories of great suffering,

00:21:56.840 --> 00:21:59.840
[Amit Varma]: how do you get a handle on how bad things are?

00:21:59.840 --> 00:22:06.280
[Guest]: Okay, so, you know, you just talked extensively about the GDP. Now, there are a lot of things

00:22:06.280 --> 00:22:12.120
[Guest]: which are not right with it. But ultimately, it is, it's a measure which everyone follows.

00:22:12.120 --> 00:22:21.620
[Guest]: And it's essentially a measure of economic activity. Okay. So how do you look at economic

00:22:21.620 --> 00:22:26.820
[Guest]: activity without looking at, let's say, the GDP number? Now, the GDP number comes once

00:22:26.820 --> 00:22:33.960
[Guest]: every three months. But there are a lot of other parameters which one can look at and

00:22:33.960 --> 00:22:40.640
[Guest]: get a sense of what is happening in the economy. And these numbers come out pretty quickly.

00:22:40.640 --> 00:22:46.680
[Guest]: So one of the things that I sort of looked at, you know, this was sometime around a month

00:22:46.680 --> 00:22:53.800
[Guest]: back in May, was revenue earning rail freight. Now, it's essentially the amount of freight

00:22:53.800 --> 00:23:01.320
[Guest]: which is moved by the Indian Railways. Okay. And in April, this came down by close to 35%.

00:23:01.320 --> 00:23:09.200
[Guest]: Now, here's the thing, what are the main commodities that the Indian Railways moves? It moves coal,

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:16.040
[Guest]: it moves steel, it moves petroleum, it moves food grains, and it moves cement. Okay. So

00:23:16.040 --> 00:23:21.840
[Guest]: if you look at railway freight as a whole, the amount of freight moved by them in April

00:23:21.840 --> 00:23:29.760
[Guest]: fell by close to 35%. This after it had already fallen by 14% in March. So one of the most

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:36.680
[Guest]: important commodity that railway moves across the country is basically coal. Okay. Now,

00:23:36.680 --> 00:23:44.400
[Guest]: coal movement fell by close to, again, 35% to around 34.6 million tonnes in April, after

00:23:44.400 --> 00:23:50.920
[Guest]: having fallen by around 14% in March. Now, what does this basically indicate? Okay. One

00:23:50.920 --> 00:23:55.520
[Guest]: is obviously, you know, coal production has fallen and because of that, lesser coal is

00:23:55.520 --> 00:24:02.780
[Guest]: being moved. But what does it tell us? It tells us largely that most factories and companies

00:24:02.780 --> 00:24:08.440
[Guest]: in India have been shut over the last more than a few weeks now, and they don't need

00:24:08.440 --> 00:24:15.640
[Guest]: electricity. Okay. Now, when you don't need electricity, you don't need coal, simply because

00:24:15.640 --> 00:24:21.560
[Guest]: most of the electricity produced in India is thermal electricity. So this tells you

00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:27.920
[Guest]: very, very clearly that most factories have been shut, most offices have been shut, thanks

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:33.600
[Guest]: to the lockdown. Then you have petroleum. You know, petroleum movement was also down

00:24:33.600 --> 00:24:40.240
[Guest]: almost 35% to around 2.3 million tonnes in April. Again, explains the lack of demand

00:24:40.240 --> 00:24:46.320
[Guest]: of petrol and diesel. Now, the interesting thing is that obviously, you know, this is

00:24:46.320 --> 00:24:51.160
[Guest]: because people were at their homes and they were not moving around. Now, the more interesting

00:24:51.160 --> 00:24:58.320
[Guest]: thing is that if people do not consume petrol and diesel, the government, the central government

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:05.640
[Guest]: does not earn excise duty on petrol and diesel. And this excise duty on petrol and diesel

00:25:05.640 --> 00:25:10.920
[Guest]: during the course of the last few years, you know, has been greater than 2 lakh crore.

00:25:10.920 --> 00:25:16.120
[Guest]: Then you look at cement movement. So, cement movement was down 90%, which tells you that

00:25:16.120 --> 00:25:22.920
[Guest]: construction activity has basically come to a standstill. It is also a very good explanation

00:25:22.920 --> 00:25:30.280
[Guest]: of the fact as to why so many people started walking from the bigger cities to their homes,

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:36.160
[Guest]: you know, in Eastern UP, Bihar, Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh, Odisha, you know, so on and

00:25:36.160 --> 00:25:41.800
[Guest]: so forth. So, the only thing, you know, the only commodity in which case the movement

00:25:41.800 --> 00:25:51.520
[Guest]: went up were basically food grains. And the food grain movement soared by 135%. And this

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:57.000
[Guest]: was primarily on account of the distribution of extra food grains, which the central government

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:02.680
[Guest]: was basically distributing. So, these grains had to be moved from parts of the country

00:26:02.680 --> 00:26:08.520
[Guest]: which had a surplus to other parts which did not. So, you know, if you looked at just this

00:26:08.520 --> 00:26:16.360
[Guest]: indicator, it could have told you in a very, very simple sort of way that all wasn't well

00:26:16.360 --> 00:26:21.480
[Guest]: with the Indian economy. Now, obviously, you know, common sense tells us in a much simpler

00:26:21.480 --> 00:26:26.640
[Guest]: way that if everybody, you know, is at home and is not going out and spending money, obviously,

00:26:26.640 --> 00:26:31.280
[Guest]: there will be a problem in the economy. But this is just a, you know, way of thinking

00:26:31.280 --> 00:26:37.760
[Guest]: where non GDP data can help us see things much more clearly.

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:42.880
[Amit Varma]: No, and this is so fascinating to me that it's almost like a piece of detective work

00:26:42.880 --> 00:26:46.640
[Amit Varma]: that you find out one piece of data and it seems like, okay, real freight, what difference

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:50.600
[Amit Varma]: does it make? But it impacts everybody's life in so many different ways.

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:56.040
[Guest]: Yeah, in fact, to be very honest, you know, I have been looking at this data for years

00:26:56.040 --> 00:27:01.160
[Guest]: now. And it sort of never occurred to me that, I mean, I always knew that this is it's a

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:07.400
[Guest]: very important data point. But I had somehow never sort of articulated it to myself that,

00:27:07.400 --> 00:27:12.480
[Guest]: you know, one could link it to almost every important aspect of the economy. You could

00:27:12.480 --> 00:27:18.080
[Guest]: link it to food, you could link it to taxes, construction, electricity, you know, these

00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:23.440
[Guest]: are things that we all used to, I mean, like electricity. Now, without electricity, there

00:27:23.440 --> 00:27:28.080
[Amit Varma]: is no survival these days. So, and, you know, what is also interesting to me, like what

00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:35.000
[Amit Varma]: you've described about what real freight indicated about everything in the economy and how everything

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:40.000
[Amit Varma]: is connected is, you know, talking about the economy from a sky high view and, you know,

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:44.200
[Amit Varma]: looking at all these different aspects of it. And now I want to zoom in to individuals

00:27:44.200 --> 00:27:49.160
[Amit Varma]: to human beings, psychology, how they think about all this, and understanding how that

00:27:49.160 --> 00:27:54.320
[Amit Varma]: ties into the economy. Now, you've written many fascinating pieces, obviously about how

00:27:54.320 --> 00:28:01.320
[Amit Varma]: psychology ties in with the economy. And also, you know, a point you often make is that what

00:28:01.320 --> 00:28:07.120
[Amit Varma]: is in an individual self interest may not be in society's self interest and vice versa,

00:28:07.120 --> 00:28:12.520
[Amit Varma]: which means that we can all behave in rational ways, as far as spending and saving and going

00:28:12.520 --> 00:28:17.360
[Amit Varma]: out is concerned. And that can harm us all in the aggregate. And there's nothing much

00:28:17.360 --> 00:28:22.840
[Amit Varma]: to do about this. And this is possibly more vivid in the time of COVID than in normal

00:28:22.840 --> 00:28:24.880
[Guest]: times. So can you elaborate on this a bit?

00:28:24.880 --> 00:28:29.680
[Guest]: So, you know, this point was basically one of the major contributions of John Maynard

00:28:29.680 --> 00:28:34.480
[Guest]: Keynes in the aftermath of the Great Depression. He basically studied the Great Depression

00:28:34.480 --> 00:28:39.680
[Guest]: and realized as to, you know, why the Great Depression became the Great Depression. So

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:45.040
[Guest]: what he basically suggested was that, you know, at an individual level, incomes drive

00:28:45.040 --> 00:28:50.840
[Guest]: spending. But at an aggregate societal level, it is spending which drives income. Or to

00:28:50.840 --> 00:28:56.000
[Guest]: put it in a simpler way, one man's spending is basically another man's income. So let's

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:03.360
[Guest]: let's sort of dwell a little deeper into this point. Let's say you are an employee and you

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:07.800
[Guest]: work for a company. Let's say you work for an IT company. The company pays you a salary

00:29:07.800 --> 00:29:13.120
[Guest]: and when the company pays you a salary, it may even give you ESOPs. And, you know, you

00:29:13.120 --> 00:29:18.320
[Guest]: use that money to buy things. I mean, you use that money to party over the weekends.

00:29:18.320 --> 00:29:24.440
[Guest]: You can, over a period of time, once you've accumulated a reasonably good amount of money,

00:29:24.440 --> 00:29:29.960
[Guest]: you can use that as a down payment for a car, for a home and so on and so forth. So income

00:29:29.960 --> 00:29:35.680
[Guest]: drives spending at an individual level. Nevertheless, you know, the question is, where does the

00:29:35.680 --> 00:29:41.560
[Guest]: company make money from? Now, the company, this company or any other company essentially

00:29:41.560 --> 00:29:48.480
[Guest]: makes money when someone else spends money to buy their goods or buy their product or

00:29:48.480 --> 00:29:53.920
[Guest]: buy their services. So in case of an IT company, it might be a project, it might be a product

00:29:53.920 --> 00:30:02.480
[Guest]: or anything along these lines. So essentially, you know, one man's spending is another man's

00:30:02.480 --> 00:30:13.800
[Guest]: income. Now, what has happened in the last few months is that large parts of the population

00:30:13.800 --> 00:30:19.660
[Guest]: are staying at home. And when you stay at home, you know, you only buy things which

00:30:19.660 --> 00:30:25.400
[Guest]: you require for your everyday use. So I mean, you may buy soap, you may buy toothpaste,

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:31.680
[Guest]: you may buy washing powder, cleaning liquid, vegetables, bread, butter, so on and so forth.

00:30:31.680 --> 00:30:37.120
[Amit Varma]: I have a feeling you're sharing your personal shopping list with me.

00:30:37.120 --> 00:30:41.720
[Guest]: I guess, yeah, I mean, it would be anyone's shopping list, Sumit. So you don't buy vegetables.

00:30:41.720 --> 00:30:46.880
[Amit Varma]: No, no, of course, of course. I was just kidding about how poor Vivek is having to do everything

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:52.880
[Guest]: himself. Exactly. So anyway, so you do this, but when you are at home, you don't go out.

00:30:52.880 --> 00:30:57.240
[Guest]: So, you know, you're not spending in restaurants, you're not going to malls, you're not watching

00:30:57.240 --> 00:31:02.960
[Guest]: movies, you're not buying new clothes, and so many other things. Like in my case, for

00:31:02.960 --> 00:31:09.640
[Guest]: almost two months, I did not buy many books. I mean, all the books that I bought were basically

00:31:09.640 --> 00:31:15.280
[Guest]: bought on Kindle. So obviously, when this happens at the societal level, it impacts

00:31:15.280 --> 00:31:22.200
[Guest]: the incomes of many other individuals. So incomes go down. It also impacts many businesses.

00:31:22.200 --> 00:31:30.040
[Guest]: So businesses, when they have to survive through this pandemic, a lot of them have fired people,

00:31:30.040 --> 00:31:37.440
[Guest]: a lot of them have cut salaries, a lot of them have withdrawn new offers, and a lot

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:42.720
[Guest]: of them have postponed dates of joining of people who were supposed to join. So all of

00:31:42.720 --> 00:31:51.080
[Guest]: this has an impact on the incomes of people, which in turn has an impact on consumption,

00:31:51.080 --> 00:31:56.760
[Guest]: and which again in turn has an impact on income, and which in turn again has an impact on consumption.

00:31:56.760 --> 00:32:02.440
[Guest]: So this is how the cycle works. Now, what also has happened, and in fact, this was already

00:32:02.440 --> 00:32:08.780
[Guest]: happening, I was earlier calling it the psychology of a slowdown, and now I'm calling it the

00:32:08.780 --> 00:32:13.520
[Guest]: psychology of a recession. Now, the difference between a slowdown and a recession is very

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:18.760
[Guest]: simple. A slowdown is essentially an economic environment where the economy is growing,

00:32:18.760 --> 00:32:23.880
[Guest]: but it's growing at a low growth rate, whereas a recession is an environment where the economy

00:32:23.880 --> 00:32:29.800
[Guest]: contracts for two consecutive quarters, which is basically a period of six months in total.

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:35.840
[Guest]: So we are not there, but we will get there by September. By September, we can officially

00:32:35.840 --> 00:32:40.840
[Guest]: say that India was in a recession for the first half of 2020-21.

00:32:40.840 --> 00:32:44.840
[Amit Varma]: But UNESCO may well proclaim it as the best recession in the world.

00:32:44.840 --> 00:32:52.360
[Guest]: Yeah, which they might, for all we know. So yes, so what will happen over the next few

00:32:52.360 --> 00:32:59.280
[Guest]: months, and it's already in progress, is that all of us will eventually come to know someone

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:07.080
[Guest]: who's lost his job, or has faced an income cut at his job, or is running a small enterprise

00:33:07.080 --> 00:33:12.080
[Guest]: which is not doing well, or is running a small enterprise which has gone bankrupt, so on

00:33:12.080 --> 00:33:17.760
[Guest]: and so forth. So basically, in a recession, people who are directly impacted by the recession

00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:21.680
[Guest]: obviously cut down on their consumption. I mean, they don't have any other way out. But

00:33:21.680 --> 00:33:26.920
[Guest]: people who are not impacted by the recession also cut down on their consumption, because

00:33:26.920 --> 00:33:32.840
[Guest]: they have this great fear of being fired or seeing a drop in their income.

00:33:32.840 --> 00:33:40.640
[Guest]: So everyone starts sort of preparing for that bad day which might come. And when that happens,

00:33:40.640 --> 00:33:46.920
[Guest]: again, spending takes a beating, and then it impacts incomes, and then it impacts spending

00:33:46.920 --> 00:33:53.760
[Guest]: again, and then more people are fired. And this is how a recession sort of spreads. And

00:33:53.760 --> 00:34:01.360
[Guest]: I think this is precisely what is happening right now. And it will continue to play out,

00:34:01.360 --> 00:34:05.160
[Guest]: at least for the, you know, for the first half of this financial year. So

00:34:05.160 --> 00:34:10.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and the interesting thing that strikes me about this very profound insight is that,

00:34:10.520 --> 00:34:15.160
[Amit Varma]: yeah, on the one hand, it's obvious that people who have lost their jobs and people whose

00:34:15.160 --> 00:34:19.920
[Amit Varma]: businesses have shut down will obviously not be spending more and therefore, because they

00:34:19.920 --> 00:34:25.520
[Amit Varma]: are not spending, others are making less income and the vicious cycle begins. But what is

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:30.120
[Amit Varma]: also happening is even people who do have their jobs still whose businesses haven't

00:34:30.120 --> 00:34:34.640
[Amit Varma]: been affected, even they will go a little easy on the spending and they'll be like,

00:34:34.640 --> 00:34:38.200
[Amit Varma]: let's take it easy. So the spending going down is not just because there's a lockdown

00:34:38.200 --> 00:34:42.840
[Amit Varma]: and people can't go out. It's not just because jobs have been lost or companies are shut

00:34:42.840 --> 00:34:47.880
[Amit Varma]: down. But even after the lockdown ends, people will go out less and perhaps correctly. So

00:34:47.880 --> 00:34:54.120
[Amit Varma]: perhaps and not perhaps but rationally, so they should go out less for the next few months.

00:34:54.120 --> 00:35:00.600
[Guest]: If you were to look at what you need to do in order to eat in a restaurant, I mean, the

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:04.280
[Guest]: rules that have been put in place, I mean, you would never go out. I mean, you'd rather

00:35:04.280 --> 00:35:06.280
[Guest]: sit at home and eat.

00:35:06.280 --> 00:35:10.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and even otherwise, you know, and so the thing is, and even with people who go

00:35:10.600 --> 00:35:15.160
[Amit Varma]: out as much as they used to, their discretionary spending the stuff they don't absolutely need

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:19.880
[Amit Varma]: to buy will go down a bit because they'll be more aware that they could be, you know,

00:35:19.880 --> 00:35:24.360
[Amit Varma]: rainy days up ahead, not in a literal sense, of course, because rainy days are ongoing

00:35:24.360 --> 00:35:26.480
[Amit Varma]: as we both of us are in Mumbai.

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:31.320
[Guest]: In fact, the interesting thing is, and when I first sort of came to know of this, I was

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:37.680
[Guest]: quite surprised. If you look at, you know, a lot of these analysts, they are also talking

00:35:37.680 --> 00:35:43.760
[Guest]: about the fact that FMCG companies might see a contraction in revenue this year, which

00:35:43.760 --> 00:35:49.520
[Guest]: is essentially unheard of. So what that means is that discretionary expenditure will definitely

00:35:49.520 --> 00:35:54.720
[Guest]: be impacted. That is a no brainer. But even non discretionary expenditure will be impacted.

00:35:54.720 --> 00:36:01.080
[Guest]: And one clear indicator of that is that people are already buying smaller packs of different

00:36:01.080 --> 00:36:06.520
[Guest]: things. I mean, that, you know, that news has come around a few weeks back.

00:36:06.520 --> 00:36:11.200
[Amit Varma]: Oh, that's so interesting. And almost so sad, you know, that in all these economic numbers,

00:36:11.200 --> 00:36:16.280
[Amit Varma]: if you look closely and use your imagination, you also get pictures of individual human

00:36:16.280 --> 00:36:21.880
[Amit Varma]: suffering. And even the way minds cloud over that you become less optimistic, and then

00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:26.760
[Amit Varma]: that pessimism just sort of reaches out and becomes more numbers because you're spending

00:36:26.760 --> 00:36:30.280
[Amit Varma]: less, others are earning less, and everything is rational. Now tell me, you've described

00:36:30.280 --> 00:36:31.280
[Amit Varma]: this vicious...

00:36:31.280 --> 00:36:34.200
[Guest]: This is, you know, it's time for a poor joke, Amit, so...

00:36:34.200 --> 00:36:35.200
[Guest]: Tell me the poor joke.

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:39.600
[Guest]: So you have all this, you know, I tweeted about this a few days back. So you have all

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:45.360
[Guest]: these B positive wala's going around, right? People keep telling you, trying to be positive,

00:36:45.360 --> 00:36:51.600
[Guest]: be positive. So, so basically, my take is that, you know, all the B positive blood group

00:36:51.600 --> 00:36:57.920
[Guest]: guys should now become C positive. Because only if you see positive, can you be positive.

00:36:57.920 --> 00:37:03.640
[Guest]: So this is like, it's in your zone, Amit. So it's better than the ones you crack.

00:37:03.640 --> 00:37:08.320
[Amit Varma]: It's horrendous. This is adding insult to injury. First, you injure me with that terrible

00:37:08.320 --> 00:37:11.680
[Amit Varma]: joke. And then you insult me by saying it's in my zone.

00:37:11.680 --> 00:37:15.640
[Guest]: Your PGS are legendary. So this is also a legendary PGS.

00:37:15.640 --> 00:37:20.240
[Amit Varma]: Indeed. Here's my question. You've described this vicious circle really well. How can it

00:37:20.240 --> 00:37:26.680
[Amit Varma]: be broken in theory or in practice, like in the past, what has broken such vicious cycles

00:37:26.680 --> 00:37:27.680
[Guest]: typically?

00:37:27.680 --> 00:37:35.240
[Guest]: So, you know, in the Indian case, we have very little experience of going through a

00:37:35.240 --> 00:37:41.760
[Guest]: recession. The last full-fledged recession was in 1979, which was also the year of the

00:37:41.760 --> 00:37:50.920
[Guest]: second global oil shock. Between 1960-61 to this financial year, I mean, assuming the

00:37:50.920 --> 00:37:56.040
[Guest]: growth contracts, this financial year, India has seen a growth contraction just five times.

00:37:56.040 --> 00:38:02.080
[Guest]: And the last time we saw growth contraction was 40 years back. Even in 1991-92, when the

00:38:02.080 --> 00:38:09.000
[Guest]: economy did terribly, we did grow. So, you know, there is very little experience of how

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:14.400
[Guest]: to get out of a recessionary environment, at least in India.

00:38:14.400 --> 00:38:19.280
[Guest]: Now, if I were to sort of talk, you know, go back to the Great Depression, because that

00:38:19.280 --> 00:38:28.680
[Guest]: is by far the best example. Countries in the West started coming out of the Great Depression

00:38:28.680 --> 00:38:35.280
[Guest]: only at the time when they started preparing for the Second World War. Now, if you look

00:38:35.280 --> 00:38:42.240
[Guest]: at the example of the United Kingdom, it was only when they started taking Hitler's threat

00:38:42.240 --> 00:38:47.520
[Guest]: seriously and then they started sort of, you know, making arms in the southern part of

00:38:47.520 --> 00:38:54.720
[Guest]: the country. That is when they started coming out of the Great Depression. In the US case,

00:38:54.720 --> 00:39:01.160
[Guest]: some of it happened when, you know, Franklin Roosevelt came up with the New Deal. But then

00:39:01.160 --> 00:39:07.440
[Guest]: the US also sort of started coming out of the recession only around the time the Second

00:39:07.440 --> 00:39:12.440
[Guest]: World War started. So, the point here is that, and this is what, you know, Keynes' insight

00:39:12.440 --> 00:39:18.360
[Guest]: was, and Keynes' insight was, in an environment where the private part of the economy is not

00:39:18.360 --> 00:39:24.160
[Guest]: spending, when individuals are not spending, when private corporations are not spending,

00:39:24.160 --> 00:39:29.280
[Guest]: the government has to become the spender of the last resort, or the government has to

00:39:29.280 --> 00:39:34.960
[Guest]: become the employer of the last resort. And, you know, Keynes also, you know, he was great

00:39:34.960 --> 00:39:41.040
[Guest]: at rhetoric, and he rhetorically even suggested that the government should essentially pay

00:39:41.040 --> 00:39:46.160
[Guest]: people to dig holes and fill them up and the money that they earn doing that, they would

00:39:46.160 --> 00:39:52.080
[Guest]: go out and spend and, you know, the economy would come out of a recession. Now, this is

00:39:52.080 --> 00:39:58.640
[Guest]: something that, you know, this was an insight which politicians, you know, loved and they

00:39:58.640 --> 00:40:02.440
[Guest]: ran with, because up until the Second World War, the government used to largely run on

00:40:02.440 --> 00:40:08.840
[Guest]: balanced budgets. They only spent as much as they earned. Now, here was an economist

00:40:08.840 --> 00:40:14.920
[Guest]: saying that it is fine to spend more money than you earn, and politicians love that insight.

00:40:14.920 --> 00:40:19.920
[Guest]: But what Keynes had also said was that the government should run surpluses during good

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:24.720
[Guest]: years, and then they should use those surpluses during bad years. Now, obviously, the politicians

00:40:24.720 --> 00:40:30.920
[Guest]: just took, you know, one part of the argument, and they ran with it. Now, to sort of talk

00:40:30.920 --> 00:40:38.720
[Guest]: about this in the Indian context. So, right now, it is important that the government puts

00:40:38.720 --> 00:40:44.240
[Guest]: money in the hands of people, and they have done that by, you know, through putting money

00:40:44.240 --> 00:40:49.960
[Guest]: in the Jandhan accounts of women. They have also brought forward the payments of PM Kisan

00:40:49.960 --> 00:40:55.480
[Guest]: and stuff like that. But these are very small amounts, okay. Now, you know, the large fiscal

00:40:55.480 --> 00:41:01.480
[Guest]: expansion as has been demanded by corporate India, and, you know, one gentleman, I think

00:41:01.480 --> 00:41:06.440
[Guest]: it was one of the builders, who even went on to suggest that the government should spend

00:41:06.440 --> 00:41:13.360
[Guest]: anywhere from $200 billion to $300 billion. I mean, that's like an astonishingly huge

00:41:13.360 --> 00:41:21.920
[Guest]: amount of money, which is, $200 billion would be close to not 10% of the Indian GDP, but

00:41:21.920 --> 00:41:27.800
[Guest]: around 7-8% of the Indian GDP. So, the question is, you know, where does the government get

00:41:27.800 --> 00:41:35.880
[Guest]: that money from? And especially in an environment where tax collections have totally crashed.

00:41:35.880 --> 00:41:40.320
[Guest]: So that is, you know, and given the fact that, you know, as we discussed, we were already

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:46.800
[Guest]: in a bad shape. So, to sort of give you, you know, the last year's budget, the government

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:55.160
[Guest]: had hoped to earn close to 24.6 lakh crore in gross tax revenues, okay, the central government.

00:41:55.160 --> 00:41:59.560
[Guest]: The revised number, when the budget for this year was presented in February, the number

00:41:59.560 --> 00:42:06.040
[Guest]: was then revised to rupees 21.6 lakh crore. What the government finally ended up earning

00:42:06.040 --> 00:42:13.000
[Guest]: was rupees 20.1 lakh crore. So, you know, you started at close to 25 lakh crore, and

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:18.880
[Guest]: you ended up at 20 lakh crore. That in itself tells you how, one is, you know, your assumptions

00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:25.160
[Guest]: have gone all wrong. And two, it is a reflection of the sad state of the economy, because,

00:42:25.160 --> 00:42:30.600
[Guest]: you know, ultimately, only if the economy is doing well, will people consume. So, if

00:42:30.600 --> 00:42:35.320
[Guest]: people will consume, then the government will earn GST. If people will earn money, the government

00:42:35.320 --> 00:42:40.840
[Guest]: will earn income tax in various ways. And when people consume, companies will produce,

00:42:40.840 --> 00:42:45.040
[Guest]: so the government will earn excise duty. So, it is all linked. So, when the government,

00:42:45.040 --> 00:42:50.280
[Guest]: rather, when we entered into COVID-19, the government finances were already in a mess.

00:42:50.280 --> 00:42:56.720
[Guest]: So, in that sense, they really couldn't, you know, do what, or they really can't do what

00:42:56.720 --> 00:43:02.920
[Guest]: Keynes' theory basically suggests. And yeah, so I guess that's the long and the short of

00:43:02.920 --> 00:43:06.520
[Guest]: it. And I mean, I'll go into a lot more detail on this as we go along.

00:43:06.520 --> 00:43:11.280
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, taking on from this, I have both a quick digression for my listeners and

00:43:11.280 --> 00:43:15.600
[Amit Varma]: three questions for you, Vivek. The quick digression for my listeners is that, you know,

00:43:15.600 --> 00:43:20.880
[Amit Varma]: when Vivek was talking about the Great Depression and the conventional thinking behind it, that,

00:43:20.880 --> 00:43:25.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, government spending helped them sort of come out of it. There is a very interesting

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:28.960
[Amit Varma]: book that I would highly recommend by the great writer Amity Shlaes called The Forgotten

00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Man, which chronicles those years and would also make you question that conventional point

00:43:33.920 --> 00:43:38.440
[Amit Varma]: of view. So, you should pick that up. I'll link it from the show notes. I have sort of

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:42.720
[Amit Varma]: three questions for you. Question one is this, that when we talk about putting money in the

00:43:42.720 --> 00:43:49.840
[Amit Varma]: hands of the people, isn't the easiest way to do that, just simply taking less from them?

00:43:49.840 --> 00:43:54.800
[Amit Varma]: That is, in terms of taxes, that first of all, to begin with, you are taking money from

00:43:54.800 --> 00:43:59.440
[Amit Varma]: everybody, not just people who pay income tax, by the way, every Indian pays taxes,

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:03.960
[Amit Varma]: even the beggar at the traffic signal pays taxes, even your domestic help, they pay taxes

00:44:03.960 --> 00:44:09.000
[Amit Varma]: when they buy salt or when they buy a sachet of soap. So everyone pays taxes. So what we

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:13.200
[Amit Varma]: really do is we take taxes from everyone, and then we give some of it back and say,

00:44:13.200 --> 00:44:18.600
[Amit Varma]: hey, we are putting money in your hands. Why not leave some of it with them? Is that something

00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:19.600
[Guest]: that makes sense?

00:44:19.600 --> 00:44:23.720
[Guest]: Of course. So, you know, one of the things that happened in September last year was that

00:44:23.720 --> 00:44:29.800
[Guest]: the government cut the corporate income tax rate majorly. And while I understood, you

00:44:29.800 --> 00:44:33.480
[Guest]: know, the reasoning behind why they did that, you know, they essentially wanted Indian corporates

00:44:33.480 --> 00:44:40.120
[Guest]: to be able to compete with, you know, companies which operate outside India. But I think what

00:44:40.120 --> 00:44:45.520
[Guest]: they should have actually done at that point of time was cut income tax rates and put more

00:44:45.520 --> 00:44:50.640
[Guest]: money in the hands of people. Now, you know, the conventional argument against this point

00:44:50.640 --> 00:44:55.640
[Guest]: is that how many people pay income tax, which is true. A large section of Indian population

00:44:55.640 --> 00:45:01.320
[Guest]: does not pay income tax. But the point is that, you know, it is the people who pay income

00:45:01.320 --> 00:45:05.520
[Guest]: tax have a lot of purchasing power in this country, right? I mean, they're basically

00:45:05.520 --> 00:45:10.600
[Guest]: the best of the lot. So when you put money in their hands, the chances that they'll go

00:45:10.600 --> 00:45:17.080
[Guest]: out and spend that money are a lot better. And as, you know, I said earlier, you know,

00:45:17.080 --> 00:45:22.120
[Guest]: generally one man's spending is another man's income. And so that would have had some sort

00:45:22.120 --> 00:45:27.400
[Guest]: of a multiplier effect on the Indian economy and would have helped us in some way. And

00:45:27.400 --> 00:45:31.000
[Guest]: it would have also helped the government because, you know, what you essentially, you know,

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:37.000
[Guest]: you lose out in the form of tax that you collect per individual, you more than make up for

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:42.840
[Guest]: it in other ways. So when people consume more, your chances of earning goods and services

00:45:42.840 --> 00:45:48.040
[Guest]: tax goes up. When people consume more, companies produce more. So your chances of earning excise

00:45:48.040 --> 00:45:53.880
[Guest]: duty go up. You know, so it would have sort of made sense at that point of time to cut

00:45:53.880 --> 00:45:58.600
[Guest]: the income tax, personal income tax rate, but that wasn't really done. Now, so one of

00:45:58.600 --> 00:46:03.960
[Guest]: the pieces I had recently written for the Mint and, you know, in that I had essentially

00:46:03.960 --> 00:46:13.400
[Guest]: suggested that the government should cut the GST rate on automobiles by 10%. I mean, that

00:46:13.400 --> 00:46:18.920
[Guest]: would be a good chunk that would lead to, you know, prices coming down majorly and the

00:46:18.920 --> 00:46:25.000
[Guest]: chances of, you know, people buying, you know, more automobiles at a lower price are significantly

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:31.320
[Guest]: better. And again, what the government would have lost in terms of the GST it collects

00:46:31.320 --> 00:46:36.920
[Guest]: per vehicle, it would have more per unit sale of per vehicle that is sold. It would have

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:42.600
[Guest]: more than made up for it, you know, in terms of volume. Also, what would have happened

00:46:42.600 --> 00:46:48.040
[Guest]: is that, you know, there would have been this huge multiplier effect. You know, automobile

00:46:48.040 --> 00:46:52.600
[Guest]: companies don't make everything on their own. I mean, there are auto ancillary units. So,

00:46:52.600 --> 00:46:57.000
[Guest]: you know, like car steerings would probably be made by some other company, tires would

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:01.320
[Guest]: come from someone else, steel would come from someone, some other company, rubber would

00:47:01.320 --> 00:47:05.640
[Guest]: come from some other company, so on and so forth. I mean, I'm not an automobile expert,

00:47:05.640 --> 00:47:11.400
[Guest]: but this is generally what I understand. So, once you get the auto sector going, you also

00:47:11.400 --> 00:47:17.560
[Guest]: get the auto ancillary sector going. So, there are huge, what economists call backward linkages.

00:47:17.560 --> 00:47:24.760
[Guest]: Then, you know, the auto ancillary sector employs a lot of contract workers. So, that

00:47:24.760 --> 00:47:29.960
[Guest]: would have helped, their incomes would have gone up, you know, vis-a-vis the situation

00:47:29.960 --> 00:47:36.280
[Guest]: now. And I mean, then they would have consumed, it would have impacted GST. And so, you know,

00:47:36.280 --> 00:47:44.280
[Guest]: so this I think is a good way of quickly putting more money into the hands of people and getting

00:47:44.280 --> 00:47:51.000
[Guest]: a large manufacturing sector going. And the multiplier effects, again, will be very decent

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:56.200
[Guest]: in this case. But I don't know whether this will, you know, I don't see this happening really.

00:47:56.200 --> 00:48:00.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, my other two questions are kind of related. So, I will kind of ask them together that when

00:48:00.520 --> 00:48:05.560
[Amit Varma]: we talk about putting money in the hands of people and that helping, you know, however,

00:48:05.560 --> 00:48:11.400
[Amit Varma]: we choose to do that, whatever the mechanics of that is, my question is twofold. Number one is

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:15.960
[Amit Varma]: that, will it really help if they don't go out and spend it and partly they may not go out and

00:48:15.960 --> 00:48:20.040
[Amit Varma]: spend it because they can't, because there is still a part lockdown and so on. And partly,

00:48:20.040 --> 00:48:24.200
[Amit Varma]: they may not go out and spend it because they are pessimistic and because there is, so to say,

00:48:24.200 --> 00:48:29.400
[Amit Varma]: a mental lockdown and a rational and justified one. That's, yeah, in fact, you go with this first

00:48:29.400 --> 00:48:33.880
[Guest]: and then I'll go to the next one. So, I think, you know, it's a very valid point. And I really

00:48:33.880 --> 00:48:41.080
[Guest]: don't have a straightforward answer for it. But what I can say is that, you know, this is a risk

00:48:41.080 --> 00:48:46.120
[Guest]: essentially worth taking for the government. In fact, there's a beautiful line in this book that

00:48:46.120 --> 00:48:52.440
[Guest]: I read recently called Radical Uncertainty by John Kay and Mervyn King, both famous British

00:48:52.440 --> 00:48:58.360
[Guest]: economists. I mean, John Kay was one of the most widely read columnists of the Financial Times and

00:48:58.360 --> 00:49:03.960
[Guest]: you know, a very well-known economist and Mervyn King was the governor of Bank of England. And

00:49:03.960 --> 00:49:08.760
[Guest]: there is a very, you know, this is a brief line in that book, which says that real governments do

00:49:08.760 --> 00:49:16.760
[Guest]: not optimise, they cope. Okay. And I think this is just the time to do that. You know, you have to

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:23.880
[Guest]: sort of take some of these decisions, which, you know, what you call a calculated risk, basically.

00:49:23.880 --> 00:49:29.400
[Guest]: So, I think it's a calculated risk and see, anyway, they're not making any money out of,

00:49:30.040 --> 00:49:34.840
[Guest]: you know, GST and vehicle sales. So, this is something that can be tried and, you know,

00:49:34.840 --> 00:49:40.120
[Guest]: I think it should work. So, and see, there are no, you know, in economics, that's what

00:49:40.120 --> 00:49:45.480
[Guest]: makes economics so interesting. And that's why so many economists get it wrong when they forecast

00:49:45.480 --> 00:49:49.800
[Guest]: things, because, you know, ultimately economics is not something where you can actually carry out an

00:49:49.800 --> 00:49:54.520
[Guest]: experiment in a lab. I mean, it's all out there in the real world. So, yeah.

00:49:54.520 --> 00:49:59.080
[Amit Varma]: And also you think probabilistically. So, just because you say something has a 55% chance of

00:49:59.080 --> 00:50:03.480
[Amit Varma]: happening and the other thing happens, that doesn't mean you were wrong. You know, the world

00:50:03.480 --> 00:50:07.720
[Amit Varma]: is probabilistic and that's how it goes. And that's a lovely quote. And you know, it reminds me

00:50:07.720 --> 00:50:12.120
[Amit Varma]: of that old cliche about not letting the perfect be the enemy of the good. And it strikes me that

00:50:12.120 --> 00:50:15.960
[Amit Varma]: one reason that governments can't optimize and have to cope is because of state capacity

00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:20.040
[Amit Varma]: constraints and all that. How much can you do? What can you do within the bounds of that? What

00:50:20.040 --> 00:50:25.560
[Amit Varma]: is worth trying? You know, and you need to think probabilistically about that. Though I think the

00:50:25.560 --> 00:50:30.760
[Amit Varma]: objection per se that people won't go out and spend seems to me to be to have a certain amount

00:50:30.760 --> 00:50:37.720
[Guest]: of validity to it. My third question. Here's the thing, Amit. You know, I'll answer this

00:50:37.720 --> 00:50:45.960
[Guest]: question in slight detail. See, ultimately, you know, the problem is that a lot of people speak

00:50:45.960 --> 00:50:54.280
[Guest]: about economics and the solutions it has to offer in a very confident sort of way. Okay. But that

00:50:54.280 --> 00:50:59.480
[Guest]: does not mean that economics has all the solutions, you know. And especially in an Indian case,

00:50:59.480 --> 00:51:06.280
[Guest]: you know, the problem is that we have been brought up writing exams where there is a right answer

00:51:06.280 --> 00:51:12.360
[Guest]: and a wrong answer, right? But life is not like that. You know, there are right answers which can

00:51:12.360 --> 00:51:18.280
[Guest]: become wrong answers and there are wrong answers which can become right answers. So, you know,

00:51:18.280 --> 00:51:23.800
[Guest]: I mean, I'm just, I mean, I won't go into detail here, but if anyone wants to understand what I

00:51:23.800 --> 00:51:29.960
[Guest]: just said in a little more detail, they should try reading Ram Gopal Varma's book called Guns

00:51:29.960 --> 00:51:36.840
[Guest]: and Thighs. He explains this very, very beautifully in that book. And the example that he uses is that

00:51:36.840 --> 00:51:43.560
[Guest]: of a cousin of his who basically did all the thinking and opened up a liquor shop. And his

00:51:43.560 --> 00:51:47.720
[Guest]: thinking seemed all right, you know, when they sort of were thinking about the entire thing,

00:51:47.720 --> 00:51:52.200
[Guest]: it just seemed like a beautiful thing to do. But when he opened it, it just bombed.

00:51:52.200 --> 00:51:59.240
[Guest]: Whereas Ram Gopal Varma opened a video rental shop without really thinking and it just took

00:51:59.240 --> 00:52:04.520
[Guest]: off. So the point I'm trying to make here is that, you know, economics does not have all the

00:52:04.520 --> 00:52:09.800
[Guest]: solutions. I mean, and it's just that a lot of economists talk about solutions in a very

00:52:09.800 --> 00:52:15.080
[Guest]: confident sort of way and people are looking for solutions. So, and this is a complaint that I,

00:52:15.080 --> 00:52:19.880
[Guest]: you know, get regularly on Twitter that you don't tell the solution. But I mean, the point is,

00:52:19.880 --> 00:52:26.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, there should be a solution. Very wise words. And actually, I must say that all the

00:52:26.600 --> 00:52:31.000
[Amit Varma]: good economists I know, and many of them have come on the show are actually pretty nuanced,

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:36.520
[Amit Varma]: but you are right that there are a lot of, I mean, there are a lot of WhatsApp economists,

00:52:36.520 --> 00:52:41.160
[Guest]: in fact, who exude so much. Especially if you follow, you know, these people on,

00:52:41.960 --> 00:52:47.640
[Guest]: a lot of them on Twitter and a lot of them on TV, you should see an economist economist,

00:52:47.640 --> 00:52:52.600
[Guest]: you know, someone who studied economics and, and probably has a PhD or something will always be

00:52:52.600 --> 00:52:57.960
[Guest]: nuanced, but a financial economist, you know, someone who's sort of may have studied economics,

00:52:57.960 --> 00:53:04.280
[Guest]: may not have studied economics, but has, is making money out of the stock market or is making money

00:53:04.280 --> 00:53:09.320
[Guest]: in some way out of the financial system. He has to be confident about what he says. He cannot be

00:53:09.320 --> 00:53:14.520
[Amit Varma]: nuanced. Yeah. And the two points to note is that one, the field that he's done well in is actually

00:53:14.520 --> 00:53:19.160
[Amit Varma]: very different from this field that he's pontificating about. And two, that he might have

00:53:19.160 --> 00:53:22.600
[Amit Varma]: been lucky in that field, like in the stock market, there's something called the survivorship bias,

00:53:22.600 --> 00:53:28.840
[Amit Varma]: which often leads to that. The other sort of quick point I'd like to add on before I get to that much

00:53:28.840 --> 00:53:35.480
[Amit Varma]: awaited third question is, you know, one thing that it's easy to do with more certainty than

00:53:35.480 --> 00:53:41.000
[Amit Varma]: the opposite of it is talk about what can go wrong, what is a bad policy or what is a bad economic

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:45.800
[Amit Varma]: decision? Like, it's very difficult to say right now, how do we come out of this, that assumption

00:53:45.800 --> 00:53:49.960
[Amit Varma]: that there is some solution, which brings us out of this, that all problems have a solution,

00:53:49.960 --> 00:53:54.840
[Amit Varma]: as you pointed out is not true. And perhaps are, you know, multiple choice questions or the right

00:53:54.840 --> 00:53:59.400
[Amit Varma]: or wrong question answer framework that we are trained to think in a school is responsible for

00:53:59.400 --> 00:54:05.000
[Amit Varma]: us thinking that way. But it is possible to point out with great certainty, what is the wrong policy

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:12.120
[Amit Varma]: to take, for example, you know, Nehru's great fan, Narendra Modi is, you know, replicating many of

00:54:12.120 --> 00:54:16.280
[Amit Varma]: Nehru's economic ideas. In fact, he's, you know, leaving aside Nehru's good ideas and replicating

00:54:16.280 --> 00:54:21.480
[Amit Varma]: the bad ones like import substitution in this whole boycott China nonsense. And that I think

00:54:21.480 --> 00:54:27.240
[Amit Varma]: any economist can confidently say, it's rubbish is just going down the wrong path, because we have

00:54:27.240 --> 00:54:32.200
[Amit Varma]: all the lessons of history to teach us that. But we'll discuss that later, you know, after we take

00:54:32.200 --> 00:54:37.000
[Amit Varma]: the break and all that, while we are still on the thread of putting money in the hands of people,

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:43.080
[Amit Varma]: such a delightful thought. My final question based on that is that one objection that is

00:54:43.080 --> 00:54:47.480
[Amit Varma]: sometimes raised to that is that, look, you can put money in the hands of people. But what the

00:54:47.480 --> 00:54:53.720
[Amit Varma]: lockdown has also done is that is disrupted, if not destroyed supply chains of companies throughout

00:54:53.720 --> 00:54:59.720
[Amit Varma]: the country. And therefore, if there aren't the number of goods and services out there are much

00:54:59.720 --> 00:55:05.800
[Amit Varma]: less. So even if you put more money in the hands of people, even if they can overcome all the you

00:55:05.800 --> 00:55:10.200
[Amit Varma]: know, the psychological barriers, it's just that there are less businesses out there and less

00:55:10.200 --> 00:55:13.320
[Amit Varma]: things being sold out there, especially in the non-discretionary space.

00:55:13.320 --> 00:55:17.480
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, so again, you know, the answer to this question was will be the same as the last

00:55:17.480 --> 00:55:23.160
[Guest]: question. I mean, ultimately, there are things that you can try. And I mean, if they don't work,

00:55:23.160 --> 00:55:27.480
[Guest]: they don't work. I mean, what do you do about it? And this again, you know, this again is also

00:55:27.480 --> 00:55:34.440
[Guest]: a reflection on our limited state capacity. It is also a reflection on how, you know,

00:55:34.440 --> 00:55:39.160
[Guest]: how we implement things like, you know, the difference between essential and non-essential.

00:55:39.160 --> 00:55:44.360
[Guest]: Okay. So I find this extremely fascinating. You know, someone should sit and I mean,

00:55:44.360 --> 00:55:49.640
[Guest]: it would make for a wonderful satire on the Indian economy that, okay. Now, I mean,

00:55:49.640 --> 00:55:56.600
[Guest]: I'll give you a very brief example. What is essential is my kirana shop guy. He's essential.

00:55:56.600 --> 00:56:05.480
[Guest]: Okay. But what is non-essential is the tempo in which stuff will be delivered to him from the

00:56:05.480 --> 00:56:12.040
[Guest]: distributor. Okay. So how is he going to supply, right? He will eventually run out of stuff. And

00:56:12.040 --> 00:56:16.360
[Guest]: which is precisely what happened in the first few weeks where they tried to figure out the difference

00:56:16.360 --> 00:56:21.640
[Guest]: between what is essential, what is non-essential. And then they tried to issue a pass. And then

00:56:21.640 --> 00:56:27.720
[Guest]: they finally said, okay, let all trucks move between States. Now, you know, so which is how,

00:56:27.720 --> 00:56:31.320
[Guest]: you know, I mean, so which is also, you know, which is, which is a big problem because, you

00:56:31.320 --> 00:56:35.720
[Guest]: know, you put money in the hands of people and then at the same time come up with rules and

00:56:35.720 --> 00:56:40.920
[Guest]: regulations, which essentially destroy the supply chain that is in place then.

00:56:40.920 --> 00:56:44.920
[Amit Varma]: No. And in fact, to add to your example, you know, that can go much further down the line

00:56:44.920 --> 00:56:49.320
[Guest]: endlessly, for example. Oh, of course. I mean, we can keep going on with this. I mean, I just

00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:53.160
[Amit Varma]: stopped it at the second level. So, yeah, we stopped it at the second level of the truck.

00:56:53.160 --> 00:56:57.080
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, if you then decide, let the truck go, you know, for many days, there were

00:56:57.080 --> 00:57:02.920
[Amit Varma]: jams on the highway because truck drivers abandoned the trucks because they could not get food to eat

00:57:02.920 --> 00:57:07.800
[Amit Varma]: because the dhabas were considered inessential and not allowed to operate. So if you really

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:12.600
[Amit Varma]: look at the whole circle of the economy, everything is essential in some way or the other.

00:57:13.480 --> 00:57:17.240
[Guest]: You know, today morning, there was this WhatsApp forward going around and I don't,

00:57:17.240 --> 00:57:23.160
[Guest]: I mean, it basically showed this bus stand in Bhayandar. Bhayandar is a suburb of,

00:57:24.280 --> 00:57:30.920
[Guest]: you know, Mumbai. The line for that bus ran it to at least two to three kilometers. So,

00:57:30.920 --> 00:57:37.000
[Guest]: you know, there was a three kilometer line to get onto a bus. So the buses are being run right now,

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:43.320
[Guest]: but the trains aren't. And this is when only a limited, very small part of the population has to

00:57:43.320 --> 00:57:52.360
[Guest]: go to office. So it's very difficult to, you know, shut down, let only parts of the economy operate.

00:57:52.360 --> 00:57:56.040
[Guest]: I mean, because if you do that, then obviously there will be other problems which will keep

00:57:56.040 --> 00:58:00.760
[Guest]: cropping up all the time. But if you open it up totally, then obviously there is, you know,

00:58:00.760 --> 00:58:04.680
[Guest]: there's a huge other problem to deal with. So, which is why I said, you know, economics doesn't

00:58:04.680 --> 00:58:10.200
[Guest]: have all the solutions or doesn't have solutions all the time. Yeah, I mean, if a planet sized

00:58:10.200 --> 00:58:15.160
[Amit Varma]: asteroid comes and hits our planet, then what solutions are economists going to find? The world

00:58:15.160 --> 00:58:21.000
[Amit Varma]: is a complex place. And at times, like, you know, 2020, so much has been happening that the dominant

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:25.160
[Amit Varma]: sentiment in the minds of many people must be, hey, give me a break. And guess what, dear listener,

00:58:25.160 --> 00:58:29.240
[Amit Varma]: we are going to do just that. We are going to give you a break. See you in about 60 seconds.

