00:59:50.360 --> 00:59:55.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and The Unseen. I'm chatting with Vivek Kaul about the Indian economy

00:59:55.960 --> 01:00:00.680
[Amit Varma]: in the times of COVID. And you know, before the break, you did that thing you typically do

01:00:00.680 --> 01:00:05.880
[Amit Varma]: problems, problems, problems, problems. And as they ask you on Twitter, where are the solutions,

01:00:05.880 --> 01:00:10.600
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Kaul? So I mean, obviously, you and I don't really have any solutions per se,

01:00:10.600 --> 01:00:15.000
[Amit Varma]: though we can probabilistically point out things that may work and may not work.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:20.680
[Amit Varma]: But when we talk about sort of the different solutions that there are for what the government

01:00:20.680 --> 01:00:26.200
[Amit Varma]: should do to lessen some of the pain, because this is not a problem you're going to solve.

01:00:26.200 --> 01:00:32.520
[Amit Varma]: Can you take me through sort of the different options that have been proposed by many and

01:00:33.160 --> 01:00:37.160
[Amit Varma]: your personal thoughts on them? For example, recently, the government came out with this

01:00:37.160 --> 01:00:42.760
[Amit Varma]: rescue package where they said, Oh, we will spend 20 lakh crore. And, you know, there was much

01:00:42.760 --> 01:00:46.200
[Amit Varma]: feverish applause. And you wrote a very interesting piece, which would, of course,

01:00:46.200 --> 01:00:50.840
[Amit Varma]: like all your pieces be which are you've written about COVID be linked from the show notes,

01:00:50.840 --> 01:00:55.720
[Amit Varma]: where the headline was six reasons why the fiscal package is more about putting people's

01:00:55.720 --> 01:01:01.480
[Amit Varma]: own money into their hands than actually kickstarting crippled economy. So take me

01:01:01.480 --> 01:01:06.120
[Guest]: through your thinking on this. Yeah, so you know, when when do editors give such long convoluted

01:01:06.120 --> 01:01:11.400
[Guest]: headlines? It feels like a very buzzfeed-y, clickbait-y kind of thing, right? No, no, no,

01:01:11.400 --> 01:01:16.040
[Guest]: when they obviously don't want to get into any trouble, right? So it's a very long headline,

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:22.440
[Guest]: which doesn't really mean anything. Okay, so basically, you know what I had written in this

01:01:22.440 --> 01:01:30.600
[Guest]: piece, and another piece that I wrote for The Mint was that, you know, how the government's package

01:01:31.240 --> 01:01:37.960
[Guest]: was, you know, like the old newspaper trick, which, you know, which, which I learned very

01:01:37.960 --> 01:01:44.440
[Guest]: early when once I started working in the media was that, you know, think of the headline first,

01:01:44.440 --> 01:01:50.680
[Guest]: okay? This is something that all good editors, old editors would tell you that think before you

01:01:50.680 --> 01:01:56.760
[Guest]: start writing, think of the headline first, and then write everything justifying the headline.

01:01:56.760 --> 01:02:01.960
[Guest]: So the government's 20 lakh crore package was a bit like that. So they first thought of this

01:02:01.960 --> 01:02:08.120
[Guest]: one big number, large number, which was 20 lakh crore, 10% of the GDP as the Indian GDP is around

01:02:08.120 --> 01:02:14.440
[Guest]: roughly 2 lakh crore. And then they went around ensuring that they, everything added up to 20

01:02:14.440 --> 01:02:21.080
[Guest]: lakh crore. Now, so first and foremost, it was a lot of people in the media called it a fiscal

01:02:21.080 --> 01:02:28.120
[Guest]: stimulus, called it an economic stimulus, which it largely was not. A fiscal stimulus is basically

01:02:28.120 --> 01:02:35.400
[Guest]: when the government spends more money or it puts money in the hands of people through a tax cut.

01:02:35.400 --> 01:02:41.160
[Guest]: So let me just give you a few very interesting examples on how the 20 lakh crore number was

01:02:41.160 --> 01:02:46.680
[Guest]: arrived at. In fact, by the time they finished adding it up, it was 20.97 lakh crore. So the,

01:02:46.680 --> 01:02:50.360
[Guest]: you know, the Ministry of Finance, you know, did really well on that front. So, you know,

01:02:50.360 --> 01:02:55.800
[Guest]: one of the first things that was announced was that the statutory provident fund contribution

01:02:55.800 --> 01:03:02.280
[Guest]: made both by the employee and the employer will be reduced to 10% of the salary. Normally it's 12%

01:03:02.280 --> 01:03:09.400
[Guest]: of the basic plus DA. So essentially this would add a liquidity support of 6,750 crore. Now,

01:03:09.400 --> 01:03:16.200
[Guest]: what does this mean? What it means is that I, you know, let's say I work for a company,

01:03:16.200 --> 01:03:23.720
[Guest]: I will contribute less to my PF and that money will come as a part of my salary and that,

01:03:23.720 --> 01:03:29.880
[Guest]: you know, I will spend in the economy. And then, you know, that is how the 6,750 crore

01:03:29.880 --> 01:03:34.040
[Guest]: number has been arrived at. Now, what has the government got to do with any of this? You know,

01:03:34.040 --> 01:03:42.200
[Guest]: how can this be a part of any package, right? I mean, it's my money. Instead of investing it into

01:03:42.200 --> 01:03:47.560
[Guest]: an employee's provident fund, I get that money in my hand and then I do whatever I choose to do with

01:03:47.560 --> 01:03:53.080
[Guest]: it. Also, because I'm getting that money in my hand, I pay a tax on it, okay? Whereas which

01:03:53.080 --> 01:03:58.840
[Guest]: wouldn't have happened when I invested money in the employee's provident fund. The other fancy

01:03:58.840 --> 01:04:05.480
[Guest]: move was the government cut the tax deducted at source and the tax collected at source by 25%.

01:04:06.040 --> 01:04:11.720
[Guest]: So if, let's say, you know, you have fixed deposits and at the moment the interest you

01:04:11.720 --> 01:04:18.520
[Guest]: earn on a fixed deposit goes over 10,000 rupees, the bank charges a 10, rather, you know, cuts

01:04:18.520 --> 01:04:24.360
[Guest]: 10% TDS, tax deducted at source. Now, what is tax deducted at source? It is essentially the

01:04:24.360 --> 01:04:32.600
[Guest]: government establishing an accounting trail. Now, if it is cut from 10% to 7.5%, what it means is

01:04:32.600 --> 01:04:39.160
[Guest]: that you get an extra 2.5% in your hands, but ultimately you have to pay tax, right? I mean,

01:04:39.160 --> 01:04:45.560
[Guest]: so there is no real, I mean, there's no money being put into your hand. Now, this move was

01:04:45.560 --> 01:04:54.440
[Guest]: expected to add, you know, 50,000 crore to the liquidity of the economy. So, my favourite example

01:04:54.440 --> 01:05:01.880
[Guest]: in this huge manipulation of numbers is something called as the Credit Link Subsidy Scheme for the

01:05:01.880 --> 01:05:08.680
[Guest]: middle income group. Now, this is essentially, you know, an interest subvention scheme offered on a

01:05:08.680 --> 01:05:14.120
[Guest]: certain size of a home loan. Now, what is an interest subvention scheme? An interest subvention

01:05:14.120 --> 01:05:19.560
[Guest]: scheme is a scheme in which the government pays a part of the interest that you're paying on the

01:05:19.560 --> 01:05:24.600
[Guest]: home loan. So, in this case, I think there are two parts. In one case, the government pays 3%

01:05:24.600 --> 01:05:30.600
[Guest]: interest. In the other case, it pays 4% interest. Anyway, so that's besides the point. So, in this

01:05:30.600 --> 01:05:36.680
[Guest]: case, the liquidity that is supposed to be added to the system is 70,000 crores. Now, what is

01:05:36.680 --> 01:05:45.560
[Guest]: happening here? What is happening here is that I take on a home loan and I put a down payment of

01:05:45.560 --> 01:05:53.240
[Guest]: whatever and then the government pays a part of my interest, okay. Now, if you look at the

01:05:53.240 --> 01:05:57.960
[Guest]: government's budget carefully, now, this was a scheme which was already there in the budget. It

01:05:57.960 --> 01:06:02.200
[Guest]: has been there for the last three years. So, I don't know why they said that, you know, we are

01:06:02.200 --> 01:06:07.160
[Guest]: extending it for 2020-21 because when they announced the budget, an allocation for this

01:06:07.160 --> 01:06:13.160
[Guest]: scheme was already there and the total allocation for this scheme in 2020-21 is just 500 crore

01:06:13.160 --> 01:06:19.960
[Guest]: rupees, okay. So, the government is actually spending 500 crore rupees and that 500 crores

01:06:19.960 --> 01:06:25.640
[Guest]: has essentially become 70,000 crores in the economic package. But that 70,000 crores is

01:06:25.640 --> 01:06:31.320
[Guest]: largely being spent by, you know, people wherein they sort of, you know, take a home loan or make

01:06:31.320 --> 01:06:36.120
[Guest]: a down payment and so on and so forth. Now, the interesting thing is that this scheme has been

01:06:36.120 --> 01:06:43.160
[Guest]: around for three years and in a three-year period, it has benefited 2,50,000 people, okay.

01:06:43.880 --> 01:06:50.440
[Guest]: Whereas this year, the government expects it to benefit 3,30,000 people. You know, it just goes,

01:06:50.440 --> 01:06:57.160
[Guest]: I mean, I find it extremely bizarre that when the economy was in an okay shape over a period of

01:06:57.160 --> 01:07:03.800
[Guest]: three years, only 2,50,000 people took the benefit of this scheme. But when the economy is expected

01:07:03.800 --> 01:07:09.320
[Guest]: to sort of, you know, get into big trouble this year, the government expects that 3,30,000 people

01:07:09.320 --> 01:07:13.080
[Guest]: will, you know, take on the benefit of this scheme. I mean, it's just beyond bizarre.

01:07:13.080 --> 01:07:22.840
[Guest]: Having said that, the biggest input, okay, into the 20.97 lakh crore package is, you know,

01:07:22.840 --> 01:07:28.760
[Guest]: comes from the RBI. So, the RBI input is a little over 8 lakh crore and it basically forms around

01:07:28.760 --> 01:07:36.200
[Guest]: 38% of the economic package. Now, what is the RBI's input? The RBI's input is the money that

01:07:36.200 --> 01:07:42.120
[Guest]: the RBI has put into the economy over the last few months. So, one thing that the RBI has done

01:07:42.120 --> 01:07:48.200
[Guest]: is that it's cut the cash reserve ratio from, I think, 4% to 3%. Now, cash reserve ratio is

01:07:48.200 --> 01:07:54.360
[Guest]: basically all the banks need to maintain a certain proportion of their deposits with the RBI. So,

01:07:54.360 --> 01:08:00.520
[Guest]: it used to be 4% earlier and it's now down to 3%. So, because of that, around 1,37,000 crore

01:08:01.080 --> 01:08:06.600
[Guest]: rupees have been released into the financial system. Other than that, the RBI has been buying

01:08:06.600 --> 01:08:13.640
[Guest]: bonds, it has cut the repo rate and so on and so forth. Now, the interesting thing is that the

01:08:13.640 --> 01:08:20.200
[Guest]: banks are actually not spending this money and, I mean, I haven't checked the data today but up

01:08:20.200 --> 01:08:26.920
[Guest]: until a few days back, more than 4 lakh crore that the banks had, 4 lakh crore rupees, were being

01:08:26.920 --> 01:08:33.960
[Guest]: deposited with the RBI because the banks had no use for that money. So, what that essentially means

01:08:33.960 --> 01:08:41.240
[Guest]: is that, you know, RBI is actually not adding liquidity to the system but is taking it out of

01:08:41.240 --> 01:08:45.960
[Guest]: the system, okay? Because banks are not, I mean, people are not borrowing, so banks are not lending.

01:08:45.960 --> 01:08:51.320
[Guest]: So, in that sense, instead of the 8 lakh crore number, the liquidity number which was added to

01:08:51.320 --> 01:08:57.880
[Guest]: the 21 lakh crore package, it had to be a negative entry of, you know, 4 to 5 lakh crore. I mean,

01:08:57.880 --> 01:09:03.960
[Guest]: I'm just taking the government's math a little forward. So, the point is, you know, a bulk of

01:09:03.960 --> 01:09:10.920
[Guest]: this so-called package was nothing but, you know, what we would call a good forward on WhatsApp

01:09:10.920 --> 01:09:15.960
[Guest]: University. Having said that, there were a few good points to it as well. One of the things that

01:09:15.960 --> 01:09:22.040
[Guest]: the government did pretty quickly was when they decided to put, you know, 500 rupees each for a

01:09:22.040 --> 01:09:30.200
[Guest]: period of three months into the accounts of all women Jan Dhan account holders. Then they also

01:09:30.200 --> 01:09:35.960
[Guest]: decided to increase the allocation to NARIGA, the Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee

01:09:35.960 --> 01:09:44.200
[Guest]: Scheme from around, I think it was 61,000 crore to more than 1 lakh crore. There was also, you

01:09:44.200 --> 01:09:50.040
[Guest]: know, extra food was distributed through the public distribution system. So, there were a few

01:09:50.040 --> 01:09:56.840
[Guest]: genuine, you know, parts to the package, but a lot of it was just simply made up. I mean, as I said

01:09:56.840 --> 01:10:02.040
[Guest]: at the very beginning, it was, you know, think of the headline first. So, the Prime Minister thought

01:10:02.040 --> 01:10:09.960
[Guest]: of a nice, you know, good headline and the Ministry of Finance then worked on justifying that headline.

01:10:09.960 --> 01:10:16.440
[Amit Varma]: So, I have two digressive observations and one digressive question. And I should point out that

01:10:16.440 --> 01:10:21.960
[Amit Varma]: actually, if I wasn't being digressive, I would be transgressive of the custom of the seen and

01:10:21.960 --> 01:10:27.320
[Amit Varma]: the unseen where being digressive is common. One observation, of course, is that this sort of

01:10:27.320 --> 01:10:32.200
[Amit Varma]: advice that editors sometimes give to think of the headline first and write the piece is actually a

01:10:32.200 --> 01:10:36.920
[Amit Varma]: hack to sort of defeat the mental block of how do you structure it or what do you do. And that

01:10:36.920 --> 01:10:43.800
[Amit Varma]: typically, as an editor, I would frown upon people who have decided what a piece is about before

01:10:43.800 --> 01:10:47.640
[Amit Varma]: they start reading it or writing it because it means you've made up your mind and you're just

01:10:47.640 --> 01:10:51.720
[Amit Varma]: going to, you know, the confirmation bias comes into play and you're just going to do everything

01:10:51.720 --> 01:10:56.040
[Amit Varma]: that supports the conclusion you've already made. But of course, we know that. And can I just

01:10:56.040 --> 01:11:01.400
[Guest]: interrupt you here once? Yeah, sure. Okay. So, I, you know, I'm just taking your point forward,

01:11:01.400 --> 01:11:07.960
[Guest]: you know, I think as when you start working in journalism, it's probably good advice.

01:11:07.960 --> 01:11:13.320
[Guest]: But as you go along, and I'm talking from my experience, I think I find the concept of a

01:11:13.320 --> 01:11:18.840
[Guest]: headline very, very limiting now. Because, you know, sometimes the headline doesn't, it just

01:11:18.840 --> 01:11:25.160
[Guest]: can't say what you have said in, let's say, a 2000 word piece or even an 800, 900 piece can be

01:11:25.160 --> 01:11:31.240
[Guest]: pretty nuanced. So I find the concept of a headline very, very limiting now because the headline can

01:11:31.240 --> 01:11:37.160
[Guest]: just say, you know, it can just give you one point, but there might be, you know, many points

01:11:37.160 --> 01:11:42.600
[Guest]: that you're making in that piece itself. So, well, you know, as an editor, I would say that

01:11:42.600 --> 01:11:48.280
[Amit Varma]: if there's a good editor, then the headline can communicate some of the nuance or at least the

01:11:48.280 --> 01:11:52.840
[Amit Varma]: fact that there is nuance, but how many good editors are there. So by and large, I know that

01:11:52.840 --> 01:11:58.200
[Amit Varma]: most, there are so many headlines that are given by editors for pieces we write, which just

01:11:58.200 --> 01:12:02.440
[Guest]: completely sort of misappointment. I mean, I mean, I agree with what you're saying, but you know,

01:12:02.440 --> 01:12:06.760
[Guest]: I'm saying something which is slightly different. What I'm saying is that, you know, when I write,

01:12:06.760 --> 01:12:12.040
[Guest]: so I see, I write pieces of all sizes, you know, from 500 words to 3000, 4000 words.

01:12:12.040 --> 01:12:16.680
[Guest]: So if I'm writing something of, you know, which is like, let's say 400, 500 words in length,

01:12:17.480 --> 01:12:21.000
[Guest]: then the headline works pretty well. I mean, I'm not, there's no problem at all.

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:26.760
[Guest]: But the moment I write a longish piece, I find the concept of a headline very, very

01:12:26.760 --> 01:12:33.720
[Guest]: limiting because even a very good editor cannot really, I mean, it's, it's just very limiting.

01:12:33.720 --> 01:12:37.960
[Guest]: I mean, because, you know, the headline typically ends up saying, you know, one or two things,

01:12:37.960 --> 01:12:41.720
[Guest]: whereas a long essay may not be just about one or two things.

01:12:42.440 --> 01:12:46.760
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. That's a digression from a digression. I won't get into that, but I will assure our

01:12:46.760 --> 01:12:52.440
[Amit Varma]: listeners that in our forthcoming weekly podcast, Econ Central, there will be no headlines.

01:12:52.440 --> 01:12:57.480
[Amit Varma]: And also, you know, and on that headline point that because that can sometimes be a bad practice

01:12:57.480 --> 01:13:03.000
[Amit Varma]: for a journalist, it can also be a bad practice for a government as in this case, my second

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:10.120
[Amit Varma]: digression would be that, you know, we keep lamenting the rise of WhatsApp economics and

01:13:10.120 --> 01:13:14.360
[Amit Varma]: the way these narratives are spread through WhatsApp and all that. And, you know, I have

01:13:14.360 --> 01:13:19.000
[Amit Varma]: been saying forever that this government doesn't care about governance, it cares about optics.

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:26.040
[Amit Varma]: But there is one sense, if one may be contrarian, in which optics is useful and optics can change

01:13:26.040 --> 01:13:32.680
[Amit Varma]: reality, which is, as we spoke in the first part of the show, that, you know, the pessimism and

01:13:32.680 --> 01:13:37.400
[Amit Varma]: the kind of mindset that times are very hard and we must not spend can actually affect the

01:13:37.400 --> 01:13:42.520
[Amit Varma]: economy is rational at an individual level, but it can affect the economy. And if you constantly

01:13:42.520 --> 01:13:46.760
[Amit Varma]: have narratives spread out there and everything is sunny and everything is great and go out and

01:13:46.760 --> 01:13:53.400
[Amit Varma]: spend, then who knows, you know, that might go a little way towards making people a little

01:13:53.400 --> 01:14:00.200
[Guest]: less pessimistic. When the financial crisis of 2008 broke out. This is precisely what George

01:14:00.200 --> 01:14:06.040
[Guest]: Bush told the American economy. I mean, you know, go to Disneyland and and then spend money. So,

01:14:06.040 --> 01:14:12.040
[Amit Varma]: yep. And my digressive question now is before we get back to various solutions that have been

01:14:12.040 --> 01:14:17.240
[Amit Varma]: proposed for what the government can do various directions, rather, I want to take a digression

01:14:17.240 --> 01:14:23.640
[Amit Varma]: to ask about a topic on which you and I have done an episode together one of the first times I think

01:14:23.640 --> 01:14:28.040
[Amit Varma]: you came on the scene and the unseen, and which you just mentioned, which is real estate, where

01:14:28.040 --> 01:14:32.520
[Amit Varma]: you spoke about how one of the packages dealt with the interest on housing loans, and so on.

01:14:32.520 --> 01:14:37.640
[Amit Varma]: And the first thought that entered my mind was what housing loans bro, because the question that

01:14:37.640 --> 01:14:43.240
[Amit Varma]: we examined in that past episode, which will be linked from the show notes, was that the economy

01:14:43.240 --> 01:14:48.200
[Amit Varma]: is so bad and demand for housing has gone down. Typically, when demand for something goes down,

01:14:48.200 --> 01:14:52.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, prices reflect that and prices go down, but the prices weren't going down then.

01:14:52.760 --> 01:14:58.600
[Amit Varma]: And they don't seem to be going down now. So can you briefly, you know, for the benefit of

01:14:58.600 --> 01:15:02.760
[Amit Varma]: listeners who haven't heard that episode, and even you might have further insights,

01:15:02.760 --> 01:15:08.040
[Amit Varma]: since the time we recorded that talk about, yeah, what the hell is happening there? Nobody's buying,

01:15:08.040 --> 01:15:13.240
[Amit Varma]: but the prices remain high. How does that make sense? I think I wrote about this recently

01:15:13.240 --> 01:15:18.920
[Guest]: somewhere and I don't remember where but what essentially has happened to real estate is that

01:15:18.920 --> 01:15:24.680
[Guest]: one that there is no demand, but there is no supply also. Okay. And I mean, I'm talking in

01:15:24.680 --> 01:15:29.640
[Guest]: very, very general terms here, right? So why is there no supply? Because, you know, a lot of

01:15:29.640 --> 01:15:33.640
[Guest]: people who bought real estate as an investment, and I'm talking about the secondary market here,

01:15:33.640 --> 01:15:38.360
[Guest]: not the primary market, you know, secondary market where, you know, when an individual buys from

01:15:38.360 --> 01:15:42.920
[Guest]: another individual. So when it comes to that market, there are, you know, many people who

01:15:42.920 --> 01:15:48.840
[Guest]: bought homes over the years and there is a price fixed in their heads. Okay. It's like the anchoring

01:15:48.840 --> 01:15:56.360
[Guest]: effect that behavioral economists talk about and they want that price. Okay. And because they want

01:15:56.360 --> 01:16:01.880
[Guest]: that price and they're not going to get it, so there's no supply. And there's no supply and

01:16:01.880 --> 01:16:06.280
[Guest]: there's no demand. It's a sort of a very unique situation which economists normally don't talk

01:16:06.280 --> 01:16:10.440
[Amit Varma]: about. But that's a secondary market, right? I mean, what percentage of the overall market is

01:16:10.440 --> 01:16:15.880
[Guest]: this? I'll come to that. So, you know, in the primary market, what happens is that let's say

01:16:15.880 --> 01:16:23.240
[Guest]: a builder builds a building and he sells the initial homes at a certain price. Okay. Now,

01:16:23.240 --> 01:16:29.880
[Guest]: if he starts cutting price after he sold those initial, let's say 20-25% of the homes in that

01:16:29.880 --> 01:16:37.160
[Guest]: building, it doesn't go down well with the people who have already bought it. Right. And it spoils

01:16:37.160 --> 01:16:43.640
[Guest]: his narrative as well. But what is happening now, at least in Bombay, I mean, and I've spoken to a

01:16:43.640 --> 01:16:50.280
[Guest]: couple of guys about this, is that builders are willing to cut prices off the record.

01:16:50.280 --> 01:16:55.720
[Guest]: So, it essentially depends on how much money they need at a certain point of time. I mean,

01:16:55.720 --> 01:17:05.080
[Guest]: how desperate they are. And if you sort of, and if you look at, and in central Mumbai where I live,

01:17:05.640 --> 01:17:12.360
[Guest]: apartments are extremely expensive, 5 crore and upwards. But there have been examples of,

01:17:12.360 --> 01:17:19.560
[Guest]: you know, apartments which used to cost 5 crore have gone anywhere between 3.5 to 4 crore,

01:17:19.560 --> 01:17:27.000
[Guest]: which is a huge, if you look at it, it's a reasonably good price drop of almost 20-30%.

01:17:27.960 --> 01:17:32.440
[Guest]: Obviously, you know, the problem in India is, and again, this is something I've written about

01:17:32.440 --> 01:17:41.000
[Guest]: extensively, is that there is no real estate price which is available directly to all of us

01:17:41.640 --> 01:17:46.920
[Guest]: in the open market. So, let's say, you know, you stay in Warsaw and you want to buy a house in

01:17:46.920 --> 01:17:54.840
[Guest]: Warsaw. You want to buy a 2BHK in Warsaw, in a building which is a decade old. So, what is the

01:17:54.840 --> 01:18:00.760
[Guest]: price? Unless you sort of call up a broker, and then you talk to five brokers, and then you start

01:18:00.760 --> 01:18:05.960
[Guest]: getting a certain sense of price. And even then you're not sure as to whether you're getting the

01:18:05.960 --> 01:18:11.800
[Guest]: right price or not. So, that is a huge problem, because ultimately, if there is no market price,

01:18:11.800 --> 01:18:15.960
[Guest]: how does the market clear? So, that remains a huge problem. And also what has happened,

01:18:15.960 --> 01:18:20.520
[Guest]: and you know, I mean, I have some sympathy for builders also now, that what has happened over

01:18:20.520 --> 01:18:26.920
[Guest]: the years is that the one, the land prices are atrociously high. And two, the kind of

01:18:27.560 --> 01:18:32.040
[Guest]: charges that state governments, you know, have put on every real estate permission

01:18:32.600 --> 01:18:38.600
[Guest]: has basically killed the market. I mean, it's again, you know, in their greed to earn more and

01:18:38.600 --> 01:18:43.880
[Guest]: more money from every project, they have ended up killing the real estate market. So, it's not just

01:18:43.880 --> 01:18:49.960
[Guest]: black money and builders which are to be blamed, it is also politicians who, one is, I mean,

01:18:49.960 --> 01:18:54.360
[Guest]: and I'm talking about the money that the state government makes, not the bribes that get paid.

01:18:54.360 --> 01:18:58.840
[Guest]: So, the money that the state governments have tried to make from real estate is just

01:18:58.840 --> 01:19:05.240
[Guest]: astonishingly huge, and that has also ended up killing the market. Very, very interestingly,

01:19:05.240 --> 01:19:11.320
[Guest]: Piyush Goyal, I mean, there was a video of the minister going around, wherein he is seen asking

01:19:11.320 --> 01:19:17.880
[Guest]: the real estate industry to cut prices, okay. Now, the point is, I mean, it's okay, I mean,

01:19:17.880 --> 01:19:22.280
[Guest]: coming from a minister, that's fine, but, you know, ultimately, there is something that the

01:19:22.280 --> 01:19:27.720
[Guest]: government also needs to do. So, one of the simple things they can do is that in order to revive the

01:19:27.720 --> 01:19:33.640
[Guest]: market, the stamp duty that needs to be paid on every sale can be cut dramatically for the next

01:19:33.640 --> 01:19:39.640
[Guest]: couple of years, okay. I mean, I know it's not a huge, it varies from 5% to 7%, but then, I mean,

01:19:39.640 --> 01:19:47.080
[Guest]: you know, when the pricing is, you know, let's say even on a 50 lakh apartment, 2%, 3% cut has a,

01:19:47.080 --> 01:19:52.120
[Guest]: you know, it leaves a decently, you know, reasonably good amount in the hands of the

01:19:52.120 --> 01:19:57.720
[Guest]: prospective buyer. So, there are a lot of things that in order to get the real estate market going

01:19:57.720 --> 01:20:02.920
[Guest]: again, I mean, obviously, a lot of things need to happen at the level of the builders, because

01:20:02.920 --> 01:20:07.880
[Guest]: the trust that the buyers had in them has completely broken down, because a lot of them

01:20:07.880 --> 01:20:13.720
[Guest]: sold apartments and disappeared, a lot of them did not deliver on time. And at the other level,

01:20:13.720 --> 01:20:19.960
[Guest]: the state governments need to be reasonable about the kind of money they hope to earn from real

01:20:19.960 --> 01:20:23.880
[Amit Varma]: estate. And I think another measure that the government has is that, you know, they have a

01:20:23.880 --> 01:20:30.360
[Amit Varma]: law by which whatever their valuation of a property is, which is a fixed point, if the buyer pays

01:20:30.360 --> 01:20:35.080
[Amit Varma]: below that, they have to pay tax on the assumption that they paid the rest, which is supposedly to

01:20:35.080 --> 01:20:40.440
[Amit Varma]: cut down the use of black money. But the effect of that is that now prices cannot fall below that,

01:20:40.440 --> 01:20:47.160
[Amit Varma]: it's almost as if the government has set a floor below. So, it's not that the prices can't, what

01:20:47.160 --> 01:20:51.560
[Guest]: is happening now in some of the larger markets is that what you're talking about is the ready

01:20:51.560 --> 01:20:56.840
[Guest]: reckoner rate. So, ready reckoner rate is the rate on which you need to pay stamp duty. Okay.

01:20:56.840 --> 01:21:02.440
[Guest]: Now, in many large cities, the market price is actually lower than the rate of the ready

01:21:02.440 --> 01:21:07.400
[Guest]: reckoner rate. Now, what happens is in that case, the, you know, the difference between the market

01:21:07.400 --> 01:21:12.600
[Guest]: price and the ready reckoner rate gets added onto your income, and you need to pay tax on that

01:21:12.600 --> 01:21:18.040
[Guest]: income. So, what that does is it just, you know, the transactions in the market come to a complete

01:21:18.040 --> 01:21:24.120
[Guest]: standstill. So, what is important here is that the ready reckoner needs to keep pace with the market

01:21:24.120 --> 01:21:28.600
[Amit Varma]: price, which is not happening. Or maybe there doesn't need to be a ready reckoner for all those

01:21:28.600 --> 01:21:33.720
[Amit Varma]: people who have watched Bollywood films and look at builders as, you know, evil people, villains,

01:21:34.280 --> 01:21:39.640
[Amit Varma]: kindly note that we are all victims of the rapacious state. And I should also say that...

01:21:39.640 --> 01:21:44.200
[Guest]: But there is another, it's again a broader philosophical point. But I think it needs to

01:21:44.200 --> 01:21:49.880
[Guest]: be made, you know, when you when you look at real estate in India, there are very few big builders,

01:21:49.880 --> 01:21:56.520
[Guest]: right? And they specialize in a particular part of the country, like BLF is a Gurgaon Delhi builder,

01:21:56.520 --> 01:22:02.360
[Guest]: it tried coming to Mumbai, flopped, it tried going to Bangalore, flopped. In Mumbai, there are

01:22:02.360 --> 01:22:08.920
[Guest]: builders who operate in specific parts of the town. So, there you have Rizvi builders in Bandra,

01:22:08.920 --> 01:22:14.360
[Guest]: you have Oberoi in Goregaon, you know, you have Godrej in Vikroli. So, the point is that, you

01:22:14.360 --> 01:22:21.080
[Guest]: know, the regulatory system that you need to manage in order to be a builder is so complicated that

01:22:21.080 --> 01:22:27.000
[Guest]: you can only specialize in a very small part of the country. And that also, I mean,

01:22:27.000 --> 01:22:31.400
[Guest]: what that does is obviously it takes economies of scale out of the equation totally. So, you know,

01:22:31.400 --> 01:22:36.280
[Guest]: if you had a builder, forget a pan India builder, I mean, even if you had a pan Maharashtra builder,

01:22:36.280 --> 01:22:41.320
[Guest]: per se, I mean, that would have some, you know, you would have a much better negotiating power

01:22:41.320 --> 01:22:45.160
[Guest]: when it came to construction of homes. So, all that goes out of the equation.

01:22:45.160 --> 01:22:49.400
[Amit Varma]: That's a great point. And you keep talking about builders and buying homes and all of that. And I,

01:22:49.400 --> 01:22:53.480
[Amit Varma]: as you were saying that, I was thinking to myself, bas kar pagle, rolaega kya?

01:22:53.480 --> 01:22:57.560
[Guest]: No, I mean, the irony is I just keep talking, you know, I've no bottle.

01:22:57.560 --> 01:23:01.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly. That's what I was saying that, you know, I would like to kind of inform all

01:23:01.960 --> 01:23:07.800
[Amit Varma]: our listeners that both Vivek and I live in rented houses. We cannot, yeah, we cannot afford to

01:23:07.800 --> 01:23:13.800
[Amit Varma]: actually own our own houses, either in the places we live or any other place for that matter.

01:23:13.800 --> 01:23:18.920
[Amit Varma]: Moving on to the sort of directions which people often propose for what the government can do,

01:23:18.920 --> 01:23:23.880
[Amit Varma]: and you know, there's borrowing money, printing money, the RBI doing this and that and blah,

01:23:23.880 --> 01:23:27.400
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah. Take me a little bit through some of them. I mean, let's start with,

01:23:27.400 --> 01:23:30.920
[Amit Varma]: it's almost become fashionable now to say, hey, the government should just print money.

01:23:30.920 --> 01:23:36.200
[Amit Varma]: And the, you know, just on the face of it, that sounds absurd to me, because we know that,

01:23:36.200 --> 01:23:41.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, if you print money, you increase the money supply, and that leads to inflation,

01:23:41.000 --> 01:23:44.600
[Amit Varma]: and that is a tax on the poor. And I just want to break it down in simple terms,

01:23:44.600 --> 01:23:49.400
[Amit Varma]: for people who may not have followed or studied that connection in the past, that if you print

01:23:49.400 --> 01:23:54.600
[Amit Varma]: money, you have more money chasing the same number of goods and services, and therefore naturally,

01:23:54.600 --> 01:24:00.600
[Amit Varma]: their price goes up. Who does this hurt? It hurts the poor, you know, it is disproportionately hard

01:24:00.600 --> 01:24:06.200
[Amit Varma]: on them, we the middle class can manage if, you know, a soap that was 10 rupees becomes 11 rupees,

01:24:06.200 --> 01:24:12.040
[Amit Varma]: which is why you sort of need, you can't just print money and spend money indiscriminately.

01:24:12.040 --> 01:24:17.480
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, that would be a solution to everything. Now, one of the things that people who are now

01:24:17.480 --> 01:24:22.120
[Amit Varma]: saying print money is that a we need money to spend. And this is one solution. And hey,

01:24:22.120 --> 01:24:27.800
[Amit Varma]: inflation won't happen. Because anyway, people are not going to spend now. And all of that. But

01:24:27.800 --> 01:24:32.120
[Amit Varma]: I would say that in the long run, at some point or the other, it will still happen, even if you,

01:24:32.120 --> 01:24:39.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, have a flat curve now to use that popular phrase of these times. So tell me a

01:24:39.480 --> 01:24:44.680
[Amit Varma]: little bit about what the thinking is behind printing money, what the nuances are, and what

01:24:44.680 --> 01:24:49.720
[Guest]: are your personal thoughts on this? I mean, this is a question that I've been constantly thinking

01:24:49.720 --> 01:24:54.920
[Guest]: about over the last three months. And in my quest to understand it, there are, you know, two things

01:24:54.920 --> 01:25:02.520
[Guest]: that I read, I found very, very helpful. One is a book by a gentleman called Randall Ray. And he has

01:25:02.520 --> 01:25:09.960
[Guest]: written this book called Modern Money Theory, Primer on Macroeconomics for Sovereign Monetary Systems.

01:25:09.960 --> 01:25:15.560
[Guest]: It's not a very easy book to read. But I mean, in case you are interested in this entire,

01:25:16.120 --> 01:25:21.000
[Guest]: you know, people who essentially support money printing, you know, this is the book to read.

01:25:21.000 --> 01:25:27.240
[Guest]: Then there's obviously this long document that Dr. Raghuram Rajan wrote. That was also very

01:25:27.240 --> 01:25:33.640
[Guest]: helpful. So I mean, I'm sort of, you know, I'm still thinking about it. But Randall Ray's book

01:25:33.640 --> 01:25:42.520
[Guest]: was a huge eye opener. And so this is again, you know, he comes from this new macroeconomic school

01:25:42.520 --> 01:25:50.600
[Guest]: called the Modern Monetary Theory. And the Modern Monetary Theory essentially, you know, starts

01:25:50.600 --> 01:25:57.560
[Guest]: with the argument or rather with the question that why do people accept paper money? Okay.

01:25:58.280 --> 01:26:02.680
[Guest]: Now, the conventional answer for that has always been that, you know, you accept paper money

01:26:02.680 --> 01:26:07.800
[Guest]: because, you know, everyone else accepts it, right? But the Modern Monetary Theory guys don't

01:26:07.800 --> 01:26:14.600
[Guest]: agree with that answer. And their answer is, you know, it's slightly more nuanced. And I think it's

01:26:14.600 --> 01:26:19.160
[Guest]: important that we sort of go through this. And I'll sort of quote, you know, small portions out

01:26:19.160 --> 01:26:25.160
[Guest]: of Ray's book. So he says that the typical answer provided in textbooks is that you will accept a

01:26:25.160 --> 01:26:30.200
[Guest]: national currency because you know that others will accept it. In other words, it is accepted

01:26:30.200 --> 01:26:36.600
[Guest]: because it is accepted. The typical explanation does relies on an infinite regress. John accepts

01:26:36.600 --> 01:26:41.960
[Guest]: it because he thinks Mary will accept it. And she accepts it because she thinks Walmart will take it.

01:26:41.960 --> 01:26:47.240
[Guest]: So I accept a dollar because I think I can pass it along to dupe some dope, is what Ray says.

01:26:47.240 --> 01:26:53.640
[Guest]: But then, you know, what the Modern Monetary Theory guys say is that people accept a national

01:26:53.640 --> 01:27:01.240
[Guest]: currency because the government allows them to pay tax in that currency. Okay. So that is how

01:27:01.240 --> 01:27:08.760
[Guest]: they sort of legalize paper money. And so that's their argument. Now, what they go on to say is

01:27:08.760 --> 01:27:18.600
[Guest]: that in developed nations where the government forms a reasonably large proportion of the economy,

01:27:18.600 --> 01:27:25.880
[Guest]: the population is willing to accept more domestic currency than what is needed for tax payments.

01:27:26.760 --> 01:27:31.160
[Guest]: Okay. The normal case, and I mean, I'm quoting out of the book, the normal case, let us say,

01:27:31.160 --> 01:27:37.080
[Guest]: in the United States or the United Kingdom or Japan, is that anything for sale domestically

01:27:37.080 --> 01:27:42.440
[Guest]: is for sale in domestic currency. These sovereign governments never find that they cannot buy

01:27:42.440 --> 01:27:47.560
[Guest]: something by issuing their own currency. So the conclusion that they draw from this

01:27:47.560 --> 01:27:55.880
[Guest]: is that in developed nations, you know, money printing can happen and it does not necessarily

01:27:55.880 --> 01:28:02.360
[Guest]: lead to inflation. Okay. Having said that, even Ray acknowledges that, you know, you have to be

01:28:02.360 --> 01:28:07.720
[Guest]: careful that these principles do not imply that the government ought to spend without constraint.

01:28:08.360 --> 01:28:13.240
[Guest]: These principles also do not deny that too much spending by the government would be inflationary.

01:28:13.240 --> 01:28:20.040
[Guest]: Okay. So there is a certain school of thought which believes in money printing up to a certain

01:28:20.040 --> 01:28:25.720
[Guest]: extent, but they also don't believe in the fact that, you know, it can go on endlessly or that

01:28:25.720 --> 01:28:32.040
[Guest]: there won't be any problems with it. Now let's concentrate on the Indian case. Now in the Indian

01:28:32.040 --> 01:28:39.240
[Guest]: case, the first problem is that the government forms a very, not a very small part, but, you

01:28:39.240 --> 01:28:46.520
[Guest]: know, not a very big part of the Indian economy. So it sort of, you know, prints money and that

01:28:46.520 --> 01:28:52.360
[Guest]: leads to inflation. Chances are people will start moving away from the Indian rupee. And that is

01:28:52.360 --> 01:28:59.400
[Guest]: something that happened, you know, post 2008 when a significantly large proportion of the Indian

01:28:59.400 --> 01:29:04.520
[Guest]: population bought a lot of gold. Okay. And, you know, it was all essentially linked with the

01:29:04.520 --> 01:29:10.040
[Guest]: government spending too much money and people buying gold. So basically what works in a developed

01:29:10.040 --> 01:29:15.240
[Guest]: economy need not necessarily work in a developing economy like India is. You know, in India, there

01:29:15.240 --> 01:29:21.560
[Guest]: is a general tendency to avoid paying taxes. Hence, you know, unlike the developed countries,

01:29:21.560 --> 01:29:26.040
[Guest]: the Indian government cannot print money and spend it in the same way as governments in most

01:29:26.040 --> 01:29:32.440
[Guest]: developed nations can. An excellent example here is that of the US dollar. Okay. Between February

01:29:32.440 --> 01:29:40.520
[Guest]: 26th and I think May 22nd, the US Federal Reserve has printed close to 3 trillion dollars. Okay.

01:29:41.160 --> 01:29:46.520
[Guest]: So basically when they started printing money, their balance sheet size was around 4.2 trillion

01:29:46.520 --> 01:29:52.120
[Guest]: dollars and now their balance sheet size is close to 7.2 trillion dollars. So they print dollars

01:29:52.120 --> 01:29:57.640
[Guest]: and they pump that money into the financial system by buying bonds. And the idea is obviously to

01:29:57.640 --> 01:30:03.720
[Guest]: drive down interest rates so that people consume more money. Okay. Now the point that you need to

01:30:03.720 --> 01:30:08.760
[Guest]: understand here is that the US dollar is the international reserve currency. It is the

01:30:08.760 --> 01:30:15.080
[Guest]: international trading currency. It is also a safe haven. Right. So whenever there is a crisis in any

01:30:15.080 --> 01:30:20.040
[Guest]: part of the world, money moves from different parts of the world and it goes to the US. So

01:30:20.040 --> 01:30:24.360
[Guest]: there is a great demand for the US dollar. In fact, one of the interesting stories that I would

01:30:24.360 --> 01:30:32.280
[Guest]: like to recount here is that in August 2011, when the SNP downgraded the AAA rating of US dollar,

01:30:32.280 --> 01:30:38.840
[Guest]: money moved from all parts of the world to the US dollar. Okay. And that was the irony of it all. So

01:30:38.840 --> 01:30:44.040
[Guest]: people like holding to the US dollar and to a lesser degree, this is also true about the British

01:30:44.040 --> 01:30:49.240
[Guest]: pound, the Japanese yen, the euros, and the Canadian and the Australian dollars. The same is

01:30:49.240 --> 01:30:54.600
[Guest]: not true about the Indian rupee. No one really, you know, beyond a point, people do not want to

01:30:54.600 --> 01:31:01.000
[Guest]: hold the Indian rupee. So what will happen is that if there is even some sense of the RBI printing

01:31:01.000 --> 01:31:07.160
[Guest]: money and handing it directly to the government, the foreign money will all start moving out of

01:31:07.160 --> 01:31:13.640
[Guest]: India. And when that happens, there will be great pressure on the rupee, your bond yields will sort

01:31:13.640 --> 01:31:20.280
[Guest]: of go up dramatically. And generally, the macroeconomic environment will be disturbed. So

01:31:20.280 --> 01:31:26.680
[Guest]: it's not really a great idea for India to print money. Also, you know, it's worth remembering

01:31:26.680 --> 01:31:34.280
[Guest]: here that the RBI used to sort of monetize the central government deficit as late as 1997. So

01:31:34.280 --> 01:31:39.320
[Guest]: what that meant was that if the fiscal deficit of the government went beyond a certain level,

01:31:39.320 --> 01:31:44.360
[Guest]: the RBI will just print, you know, money and bring down the fiscal deficit. But since in 1997,

01:31:44.360 --> 01:31:50.200
[Guest]: the RBI entered into agreement with the government and it doesn't happen like that anymore. And

01:31:50.200 --> 01:31:54.600
[Guest]: because of that, what has happened is that, you know, interest rates sort of went up over the

01:31:54.600 --> 01:32:00.760
[Guest]: years and people actually saved a lot of money and that led to investments and that, you know,

01:32:00.760 --> 01:32:07.800
[Guest]: helped the economy at large. So if the government prints money, you're essentially starting to

01:32:07.800 --> 01:32:15.080
[Guest]: question the structure that was put in place and that has worked well over the years. So this is,

01:32:15.080 --> 01:32:21.720
[Guest]: and then there's a beautiful argument that I think Raghuram Rajan made in the brief paper that

01:32:22.440 --> 01:32:29.480
[Guest]: he wrote and this is how he put it. So let's say the RBI prints money, okay, and hands it over to

01:32:29.480 --> 01:32:35.240
[Guest]: the government. Now, so basically the money goes into the government account and then the government

01:32:35.240 --> 01:32:39.720
[Guest]: spends the money on something. Now, when the government spends the money on something,

01:32:39.720 --> 01:32:48.120
[Guest]: you know, incomes of people go up and money comes into their hands and then they go and spend that

01:32:48.120 --> 01:32:53.560
[Guest]: money and so that money lands up with some, you know, shopkeepers all over the country. And given

01:32:53.560 --> 01:33:00.120
[Guest]: that, you know, in an environment where people are not willing to spend, that money ultimately

01:33:00.120 --> 01:33:07.880
[Guest]: comes back to the banks, okay, and banks are not able to lend that money and then they deposit the

01:33:07.880 --> 01:33:15.480
[Guest]: money with the RBI and the RBI pays them interest on the money that they deposit with it and that

01:33:15.480 --> 01:33:21.480
[Guest]: rate of interest is called the reverse repo rate, okay. So essentially what will happen is that if

01:33:21.480 --> 01:33:27.800
[Guest]: the government prints and pumps money into the economy, the velocity of money is so low at this

01:33:27.800 --> 01:33:33.880
[Guest]: point of time that money will not change hands and it will ultimately end up with the RBI and the

01:33:33.880 --> 01:33:39.320
[Guest]: RBI will end up paying interest on the printed money and if the RBI ends up paying interest on

01:33:39.320 --> 01:33:45.400
[Guest]: printed money, it obviously earns less money during the course of the year and then it gives

01:33:45.400 --> 01:33:50.360
[Guest]: a lower dividend to the government, okay. Now, banks also lose out on money because

01:33:50.360 --> 01:33:55.880
[Guest]: if the government was financing its fiscal deficit through, you know, by issuing bonds,

01:33:55.880 --> 01:34:02.200
[Guest]: the banks would have earned a higher rate of interest than what they would earn by depositing

01:34:02.200 --> 01:34:08.760
[Guest]: money into with the RBI at the reverse repo rate. So there are a lot of these interesting points

01:34:08.760 --> 01:34:15.800
[Guest]: which, you know, a lot of people who believe in the modern monetary theory either do not understand

01:34:15.800 --> 01:34:20.840
[Guest]: or they don't talk about it. But if you read up guys who actually, you know, who believe in modern

01:34:20.840 --> 01:34:27.080
[Amit Varma]: monetary theory, they offer all these reasons very, very clearly. Yeah, and it kind of strikes me as

01:34:27.080 --> 01:34:32.440
[Amit Varma]: fairly amusing that firstly RBI prints money and then it pays interest on the same money,

01:34:32.440 --> 01:34:36.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, the seen and the unseen right there. And, you know, I will, of course, endorse your

01:34:36.360 --> 01:34:40.200
[Amit Varma]: conclusion of saying that printing money is a bad idea and just because something works in

01:34:40.200 --> 01:34:44.280
[Amit Varma]: developed countries doesn't mean it will work in developing countries. But I will also add to that

01:34:44.280 --> 01:34:50.680
[Amit Varma]: that I'm not even sure it can work in developed countries. The jury is out on that. This is just

01:34:50.680 --> 01:34:55.960
[Guest]: one theory among many. So see, I'll tell you why modern monetary theory has picked up in the last,

01:34:55.960 --> 01:35:01.080
[Guest]: at least in the last 12, 13 years, you know. So all the central banks, the western central banks

01:35:01.080 --> 01:35:07.880
[Guest]: have printed a lot of money, but that has not led to conventional consumer price inflation.

01:35:07.880 --> 01:35:13.800
[Guest]: Okay, so which is why the MMT walas are, you know, bullish right now and sort of, they have a market.

01:35:13.800 --> 01:35:21.240
[Guest]: But what they forget is that the reason that there has been very little consumer price inflation

01:35:21.240 --> 01:35:27.480
[Guest]: is because China has become the factory of the world. Okay, and they have really, you know,

01:35:27.480 --> 01:35:32.680
[Guest]: increased their productivity and driven down prices globally. The second thing what they don't

01:35:32.680 --> 01:35:37.320
[Guest]: talk about is the fact that even though there has been no consumer price inflation, there has been

01:35:37.320 --> 01:35:42.280
[Guest]: huge asset inflation all across the world. I mean, you know, stock markets have been going up for

01:35:42.280 --> 01:35:48.680
[Guest]: years without company earnings going up. I mean, if you look at the Indian market in the last eight

01:35:48.680 --> 01:35:55.480
[Guest]: years, price has gone up at a much faster rate than the earnings. So, and the gap keeps increasing

01:35:55.480 --> 01:36:01.080
[Guest]: every year. So obviously there is inflation, but it's just that it is not conventional consumer

01:36:01.080 --> 01:36:07.000
[Guest]: price inflation. It is inflation which is reflected in the assets that you, you know, that you buy all

01:36:07.000 --> 01:36:08.280
[Guest]: across the world. So.

01:36:08.280 --> 01:36:12.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and they're both great points and to sort of add to the first point, you know, of consumer

01:36:12.600 --> 01:36:17.400
[Amit Varma]: price inflation not being reflected because China is sort of the factory of the world. We also don't

01:36:17.400 --> 01:36:21.960
[Amit Varma]: see the counterfactual. If these governments hadn't printed so much money, would prices have

01:36:21.960 --> 01:36:27.080
[Amit Varma]: been lower, even lower, we simply don't know the counterfactual. And therefore, I find all of this

01:36:27.880 --> 01:36:33.320
[Guest]: Inflation is a very individual thing, Amit, you know, I mean, it depends on what exactly your

01:36:33.320 --> 01:36:39.400
[Guest]: consumer basket is at any point of time. I mean, if you have kids, they go to a good school. I mean,

01:36:39.400 --> 01:36:45.000
[Guest]: you have a pretty good rate of inflation because school fee, you know, goes up every year, the cost

01:36:45.000 --> 01:36:50.920
[Guest]: of educating a child, all the activities that come with it. I mean, these days, it's not just enough

01:36:50.920 --> 01:36:55.480
[Guest]: to send your, you know, kid to school and then forget about it. I mean, there are 10 other things

01:36:55.480 --> 01:36:57.320
[Guest]: that he or she needs to be a part of.

01:36:57.320 --> 01:37:02.120
[Amit Varma]: A fascinating example to come up in a discussion between two people who don't have kids.

01:37:02.120 --> 01:37:08.280
[Guest]: Let me get judgmental about the entire thing.

01:37:09.000 --> 01:37:14.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so let's kind of move on from, you know, one direction that it is often proposed the

01:37:14.280 --> 01:37:18.600
[Amit Varma]: government can go in which is printing money to another one, which is borrowing money.

01:37:18.600 --> 01:37:24.280
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about the pros and cons of that approach. And what is the thinking behind

01:37:24.280 --> 01:37:24.760
[Guest]: that?

01:37:24.760 --> 01:37:29.080
[Guest]: Okay, you know, when the government borrows money, the good thing is that

01:37:29.080 --> 01:37:35.480
[Guest]: it is setting a sort of a benchmark interest rate for the entire financial system, right?

01:37:35.480 --> 01:37:40.840
[Guest]: Because the government borrows at the lowest rate, you know, lending to the government is

01:37:40.840 --> 01:37:47.400
[Guest]: the least risky form of lending on most days. So, that is one good thing, that it is borrowing at

01:37:47.400 --> 01:37:53.800
[Guest]: a rate which the market is sort of deciding on. The problem with borrowing, now there are multiple

01:37:53.800 --> 01:37:58.200
[Guest]: problems with borrowing as well. So, the first problem is if you borrow too much and again,

01:37:58.200 --> 01:38:02.600
[Guest]: you know, this is why a lot of people recommend money printing, is when you borrow too much as

01:38:02.600 --> 01:38:07.160
[Guest]: a government, you crowd out the private borrowers, right? So, when you crowd out the private borrowers,

01:38:07.160 --> 01:38:12.200
[Guest]: the entire interest rate in the financial system tends to go up. So, which is why a lot of

01:38:12.200 --> 01:38:16.520
[Guest]: economists right now have been, you know, saying that, you know, the government should print money

01:38:16.520 --> 01:38:22.440
[Guest]: and they should monetize and this and that. In fact, interestingly, it is not that RBI is not

01:38:22.440 --> 01:38:27.080
[Guest]: printing money and not monetizing the fiscal deficit, but they're not doing so directly. So,

01:38:27.080 --> 01:38:32.440
[Guest]: what they do is, you know, there are primary dealers which basically create the market in

01:38:32.440 --> 01:38:38.920
[Guest]: bonds. I mean, they primarily, so the RBI is using these primary dealers to buy government bonds.

01:38:38.920 --> 01:38:44.440
[Guest]: So, the market has an indication that the RBI is buying bonds, but no one can say very, very

01:38:44.440 --> 01:38:49.960
[Guest]: clearly that the RBI is. But there are, I think, at least two central bank governors, D Subba Rao

01:38:49.960 --> 01:38:56.840
[Guest]: and Raghuram Rajan, who have both gone on record to say that the RBI is printing money and monetizing

01:38:56.840 --> 01:39:01.320
[Guest]: a certain part of the deficit, though it is doing so indirectly. And which is good because when

01:39:01.320 --> 01:39:07.080
[Guest]: you're doing it indirectly, at least you are paying the market rate of interest to some extent.

01:39:07.080 --> 01:39:11.720
[Guest]: Now, the problem is when you borrow more, one is the crowding out part where the interest rates

01:39:11.720 --> 01:39:16.120
[Guest]: go up. But then, you know, right now, I don't think that is much of an issue because the private

01:39:16.120 --> 01:39:22.280
[Guest]: sector is really not into borrowing right now. The other thing that happens is that the rating

01:39:22.280 --> 01:39:29.240
[Guest]: agencies tend to follow the debt-to-GDP ratio while deciding on the rating. Now, in an environment

01:39:29.240 --> 01:39:36.680
[Guest]: where your GDP is contracting and your debt is going up, so when the debt-to-GDP ratio goes

01:39:36.680 --> 01:39:42.600
[Guest]: beyond a certain level, then there is a cut in the rating. And right now, India is just barely

01:39:42.600 --> 01:39:49.720
[Guest]: investment grade, one cut and we become non-investment. And if that happens, a lot of,

01:39:49.720 --> 01:39:54.600
[Guest]: you know, serious foreign money, pension fund money and all that, will move out both of the

01:39:54.600 --> 01:40:01.320
[Guest]: Indian bond market as well as the Indian stock market, which will create problems for, you know,

01:40:01.320 --> 01:40:07.400
[Guest]: everyone. But having said that, the thing here is that I think the lesser evil right now is to

01:40:07.400 --> 01:40:11.480
[Guest]: borrow money than to print money because the government really doesn't have a choice. You know,

01:40:11.480 --> 01:40:15.960
[Guest]: the tax collections have totally collapsed. I mean, if you look at the April numbers of the

01:40:15.960 --> 01:40:22.920
[Guest]: central government, the tax collections are down by around 44%. GST collections have collapsed 87%

01:40:23.720 --> 01:40:31.640
[Guest]: to around 5,934 crore, if I remember the number correctly. So, that's the lesser evil right now.

01:40:31.640 --> 01:40:38.600
[Guest]: Having said that, okay, there are other repercussions to the government not borrowing

01:40:38.600 --> 01:40:43.080
[Guest]: more money but the fiscal deficit going up. And this is important to explain because,

01:40:43.080 --> 01:40:48.680
[Guest]: you know, as we said at the very beginning that the, you know, economics has, it seems to operate

01:40:48.680 --> 01:40:53.560
[Guest]: at a very, very high level, but it has impacts on all of us. And a lot of us don't understand

01:40:53.560 --> 01:40:59.320
[Guest]: those impacts. So, you know, look at the fact that the fiscal deficits of the state governments

01:40:59.320 --> 01:41:03.000
[Guest]: as well as central governments will go up this year, right, because they are not earning as

01:41:03.000 --> 01:41:08.840
[Guest]: much tax as they had hoped to. Now, the repercussions of that can be seen immediately.

01:41:08.840 --> 01:41:15.080
[Guest]: Now, look at the fact that the government has decided not to pay the increase in Dearness

01:41:15.080 --> 01:41:19.240
[Guest]: Allowance as well as Dearness Reliefs for the salaried government employees as well as the

01:41:19.240 --> 01:41:25.800
[Guest]: retired government employees up until July 2021. So, that, you know, one estimate suggested would

01:41:25.800 --> 01:41:31.240
[Guest]: lead to a saving of around 38,000 crore. This is the central government. A lot of state governments

01:41:31.240 --> 01:41:35.480
[Guest]: have followed the central government and if, I guess, all state governments follow the central

01:41:35.480 --> 01:41:41.000
[Guest]: government, that saves another 82,000 crore. Now, this is money that the government employees would

01:41:41.000 --> 01:41:46.840
[Guest]: have earned, but they did not. Now, government employees are one sort of class of employees

01:41:47.400 --> 01:41:54.920
[Guest]: who do not feel the pain of slow economic growth much, okay, but this time they are.

01:41:54.920 --> 01:42:00.680
[Guest]: The second thing is the price of petrol and diesel, you know. Even though, you know, between,

01:42:00.680 --> 01:42:06.600
[Guest]: I think, in January, the price of crude oil was around $65. Currently, it's around $40,

01:42:06.600 --> 01:42:12.920
[Guest]: but the price of petrol and diesel is still what it was in January. So, the reason for that is that

01:42:12.920 --> 01:42:18.360
[Guest]: the excise duty that the central government charges and the sales tax that the state government

01:42:18.360 --> 01:42:22.760
[Guest]: charges, both of them have sort of been ramped up. So, obviously, you and I are paying for that,

01:42:22.760 --> 01:42:29.240
[Guest]: right? The third thing is when the RBI has printed and pumped a lot of money into the

01:42:29.240 --> 01:42:34.280
[Guest]: financial system, that has led to the fixed deposit interest rates coming down. In fact,

01:42:34.280 --> 01:42:41.560
[Guest]: I was very, very surprised while writing a piece a couple of days back that a two-year fixed deposit

01:42:42.120 --> 01:42:49.720
[Guest]: for Kotak Mahindra Bank pays you just 4.75 percent per year. And, in fact, the rate of interest was

01:42:49.720 --> 01:42:53.880
[Guest]: even lower than that of the State Bank of India, which was, normally, it's the State Bank of India

01:42:53.880 --> 01:43:00.600
[Guest]: which sets the benchmark. So, 5.1 percent. So, interest rates on fixed deposits have come down.

01:43:00.600 --> 01:43:06.680
[Guest]: Obviously, you and I will have to pay for that. What will also happen is that the interest rates

01:43:06.680 --> 01:43:13.720
[Guest]: on small savings schemes will automatically come down in the months to come. So, it's not like

01:43:13.720 --> 01:43:18.680
[Guest]: only the government gets impacted or only the companies get impacted. I mean, you and I also

01:43:18.680 --> 01:43:24.680
[Guest]: get impacted through all these things. And if the government sort of, you know, decides to start

01:43:24.680 --> 01:43:31.240
[Guest]: printing money, there is an extreme danger that money will move out of the stock market and it's

01:43:31.240 --> 01:43:36.360
[Guest]: essentially foreign money and SIP money which has kept the stock market going. So, if the foreign

01:43:36.360 --> 01:43:42.600
[Guest]: money goes out, it's only the SIP money which is left. Which, you know, brings me to another

01:43:42.600 --> 01:43:47.160
[Amit Varma]: digression which is something that, you know, people have been baffled about for the last few

01:43:47.160 --> 01:43:51.960
[Amit Varma]: years, in fact, that the economy keeps going down and the stock market keeps going up. So, in a

01:43:51.960 --> 01:43:57.000
[Guest]: nutshell... I have an explanation for that. And this is, again, something I realized only recently.

01:43:57.000 --> 01:44:02.520
[Guest]: In fact, in the last three years, the stock market has primarily been driven by the SIP investors.

01:44:02.520 --> 01:44:07.080
[Guest]: So, it's the SIP investors who bring in money, the market goes up, more SIP investors come in,

01:44:07.080 --> 01:44:12.520
[Guest]: and it's a perfect, what you call, a naturally occurring Ponzi scheme. And I should point out

01:44:12.520 --> 01:44:17.160
[Amit Varma]: here to all our listeners that one of the very popular episodes that Vivek and I have done together

01:44:17.160 --> 01:44:22.680
[Amit Varma]: is on Ponzi schemes that will be linked from the show notes. You will find much to relate to

01:44:22.680 --> 01:44:26.920
[Amit Varma]: when you listen to that and think of the modern world in which we live, especially the way

01:44:26.920 --> 01:44:34.360
[Guest]: the state operates. One last point. So, all this essentially, you know, comes back to the fact that

01:44:34.920 --> 01:44:39.960
[Guest]: we have been in a mess before COVID. Because if we had not been in a mess before COVID,

01:44:39.960 --> 01:44:46.120
[Guest]: we would have had, you know, still some tax inflows coming in. But because we were already

01:44:46.120 --> 01:44:50.760
[Guest]: in a mess, this is sort of, you know, that has accentuated the problem.

01:44:50.760 --> 01:44:56.840
[Amit Varma]: So, here's sort of one question, which is that we have been discussing the various ways in which

01:44:56.840 --> 01:45:03.160
[Amit Varma]: governments can raise money, which is they can print it or borrow it, or just announce on WhatsApp

01:45:03.160 --> 01:45:08.280
[Amit Varma]: that they have it. But whatever the government does to get money, once it has it, what should

01:45:08.280 --> 01:45:13.640
[Amit Varma]: it do with it? You know, if when you consider the unseen effects of all kinds of spending that

01:45:14.280 --> 01:45:19.000
[Amit Varma]: it can do, including, of course, the unseen effect of what the money could have achieved,

01:45:19.000 --> 01:45:23.240
[Amit Varma]: had it been left with the people that it's been taken from whatever percentage of that is

01:45:24.120 --> 01:45:29.080
[Amit Varma]: tax. But apart from that, what should they actually do with it? What is a sensible thing

01:45:29.080 --> 01:45:34.600
[Amit Varma]: to do here? Should we not cut area spending in many areas where we spend too much? And what

01:45:34.600 --> 01:45:39.320
[Guest]: are the areas in which we need to pump money? I think it is already happening. I mean, if you

01:45:39.320 --> 01:45:44.440
[Guest]: if you read the newspapers carefully, I think most of the major projects have been put on hold,

01:45:45.000 --> 01:45:50.360
[Guest]: and they don't have the money to do anything else. So, right now, you know, most of the money

01:45:50.360 --> 01:45:58.920
[Guest]: is going towards tackling COVID-19. So, I think one of the things that I suggested in the first

01:45:58.920 --> 01:46:03.560
[Guest]: piece that I wrote on what the government can do to tackle COVID-19, I mean, I've written many

01:46:03.560 --> 01:46:09.400
[Guest]: written many pieces since then, was the fact that money needs to be put into the hands of people,

01:46:09.400 --> 01:46:15.000
[Guest]: right? So, the government has essentially put 1500 rupees over a period of three months

01:46:15.000 --> 01:46:19.640
[Guest]: into the hands of female Jan Dhan account holders. So, I mean, their number is around 20 crore,

01:46:19.640 --> 01:46:26.920
[Guest]: whereas the total Jan Dhan accounts amount to around 38 crore. I think this is not the time

01:46:26.920 --> 01:46:32.440
[Guest]: to sort of differentiate between, you know, man and woman, and money should have been put into

01:46:32.440 --> 01:46:37.640
[Guest]: all Jan Dhan accounts. And this is something I think which needs to continue through the course

01:46:37.640 --> 01:46:44.680
[Guest]: of this year. Now, people will come around and tell you, you know, what is 500 rupees? But then

01:46:44.680 --> 01:46:49.400
[Guest]: again, at the end of the day, some money is better than no money, right? And the government cannot,

01:46:49.400 --> 01:46:54.440
[Guest]: I mean, obviously, there are limitations, it can only do things within a certain limit. And given

01:46:54.440 --> 01:47:01.400
[Guest]: that, I think if it has the money, the thing it needs to do right now is to sort of put more and

01:47:01.400 --> 01:47:06.920
[Guest]: more money in the hands of people. And you know, I mean, people will say, okay, but what if they

01:47:06.920 --> 01:47:12.360
[Guest]: save it? And I mean, that's fine. I mean, even if they save it, it will be there for them to spend

01:47:12.360 --> 01:47:18.600
[Guest]: at a certain point of time. I mean, that I think is the only thing that will work right now. And

01:47:18.600 --> 01:47:22.760
[Guest]: so obviously, the problem is targeting, you know, a lot of people have suggested that the government

01:47:22.760 --> 01:47:26.760
[Guest]: should put, I think I was reading a comment somewhere, one of these business guys said that

01:47:26.760 --> 01:47:32.600
[Guest]: 5000 rupees should be put into the accounts of all migrants. But how do you identify a migrant,

01:47:32.600 --> 01:47:38.920
[Guest]: right? So, this is also the time to sort of build slightly more robust systems where better

01:47:38.920 --> 01:47:44.600
[Guest]: targeting can be carried out. Now, the problem again with that is, you know, you go back to

01:47:45.480 --> 01:47:52.360
[Guest]: IT security and, you know, all those issues start to, privacy and all those issues start to crop

01:47:52.360 --> 01:47:59.400
[Guest]: up. So, basically, you know, the state capacity in India is very, very limited. And because we,

01:48:00.040 --> 01:48:04.440
[Guest]: the government wants to do way too many things, which it shouldn't be doing,

01:48:05.480 --> 01:48:10.360
[Guest]: it does not end up doing those things that it should be doing well. This is a good time to

01:48:10.360 --> 01:48:16.680
[Guest]: tackle that. And one thing that can easily be done is, you know, the government owns a tremendous

01:48:16.680 --> 01:48:21.240
[Guest]: amount of land. And this is not, you know, Rajesh Jain's version of where he suggests everything

01:48:21.240 --> 01:48:28.680
[Guest]: should be sold. But, you know, there is a lot of land with the government and public sector

01:48:28.680 --> 01:48:35.080
[Guest]: enterprises, and this land can easily be sold. Land prices can be brought down, real estate prices

01:48:35.080 --> 01:48:41.720
[Guest]: can be brought down. And, you know, we talked in the beginning about a GST rate cut essentially

01:48:41.720 --> 01:48:47.640
[Guest]: helping the automobile industry, right? Because the automobile industry has many backward and

01:48:47.640 --> 01:48:54.600
[Guest]: forward linkages. The real estate sector has 250 forward and backward linkages. So, what that

01:48:54.600 --> 01:49:00.440
[Guest]: essentially means is that if the real estate sector starts to do well, there are 250 other

01:49:00.440 --> 01:49:05.480
[Guest]: sectors which have the potential to do well. I mean, you know, so obviously, you know, you would

01:49:05.480 --> 01:49:11.080
[Guest]: need sand, you will need cement, you will need wood, you will need glass to sort of build a home.

01:49:11.080 --> 01:49:15.960
[Guest]: And then once a home is being bought, people will have to furnish it. In order to buy a home,

01:49:15.960 --> 01:49:23.080
[Guest]: people will need a bank loan. So, I think it's very, very important that, you know, one is to

01:49:23.080 --> 01:49:30.840
[Guest]: address the post-COVID economic scenario, and also to sort of cash in on India's so-called

01:49:30.840 --> 01:49:36.440
[Guest]: demographic dividend, that we get a real estate sector, right? And this is the opportunity to do

01:49:36.440 --> 01:49:42.440
[Amit Varma]: it. So, I have three digressions, the third of which will lead to a question. And hopefully,

01:49:42.440 --> 01:49:47.320
[Amit Varma]: we can avoid further digressions while these three digressions are being aired. And then we'll get to

01:49:47.320 --> 01:49:52.120
[Amit Varma]: the question. First digression, of course, is that I have a great two-hour episode with Rajesh Jain,

01:49:52.120 --> 01:49:57.240
[Amit Varma]: whose proposal essentially was that, look, we sit on humongous amounts of public land,

01:49:57.240 --> 01:50:02.280
[Amit Varma]: which are being put to no good use. And if the government starts selling that off, one,

01:50:02.280 --> 01:50:06.040
[Amit Varma]: it will have a lot of money, which will be helpful, especially in a crisis like this,

01:50:06.040 --> 01:50:11.320
[Amit Varma]: huge amounts of money. And two, it will also, you know, land prices will go down because the supply

01:50:11.320 --> 01:50:15.880
[Amit Varma]: will go up. And that will be great for common people. A digression within this digression is

01:50:15.880 --> 01:50:21.960
[Amit Varma]: another way to make the supply of land go up and land prices go down, is to reduce the sort of

01:50:21.960 --> 01:50:28.280
[Amit Varma]: ridiculous laws like FSI and rent control that we have, especially in our big cities. Digression one

01:50:28.280 --> 01:50:33.720
[Amit Varma]: over. Digression two is a rant, which is that forget government spending, a lot of money was

01:50:33.720 --> 01:50:40.520
[Amit Varma]: basically recently raised from contributions to a fund called PM Cares. None of that is being said.

01:50:40.520 --> 01:50:44.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, it is opaque. None of that has been spent. We don't know where it's going and what

01:50:44.520 --> 01:50:49.720
[Amit Varma]: it's for, which leads me to digression three. There is one area where the government should

01:50:49.720 --> 01:50:54.840
[Amit Varma]: have spent money and, you know, got it right in the last three months, which is the plight of

01:50:54.840 --> 01:50:59.320
[Amit Varma]: migrant labourers throughout the country. It is okay to say in the last week of March when the

01:50:59.320 --> 01:51:04.760
[Amit Varma]: lockdown started that, okay, we were blindsided, it did not strike us. But, you know, that went

01:51:04.760 --> 01:51:11.000
[Amit Varma]: on for weeks and weeks. And that's a humanitarian crisis. It's absolutely unconscionable. And the

01:51:11.000 --> 01:51:15.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of question I'll get to and I was discussing this last week in my episode on lockdowns and

01:51:15.880 --> 01:51:20.520
[Amit Varma]: COVID-19 with the brilliant Anup Malani. And the larger point we discussed there was,

01:51:21.080 --> 01:51:26.360
[Amit Varma]: which will lead to the question that I come to, is that a lot of this migrant labour hasn't just

01:51:26.360 --> 01:51:30.440
[Amit Varma]: gone back on a temporary basis that when this crisis ends, they will come back and everything

01:51:30.440 --> 01:51:36.600
[Amit Varma]: will be okay again. There is a deep loss of trust in the system. You know, they found themselves

01:51:36.600 --> 01:51:42.040
[Amit Varma]: starving, they found themselves out of jobs, and they found the government unwilling to help in

01:51:42.040 --> 01:51:47.480
[Amit Varma]: any way. On the contrary, putting barriers in their way, which has led to a loss of not just

01:51:47.480 --> 01:51:53.560
[Amit Varma]: livelihoods, but also lives and also hope. Many of these people may not come back. You know,

01:51:53.560 --> 01:51:59.240
[Amit Varma]: broadly from out of this sort of incredible tragedy that has happened, what do you think the

01:51:59.240 --> 01:52:02.840
[Guest]: economic impacts of that could be? I know, I mean, you know, I've been thinking about this for a

01:52:02.840 --> 01:52:08.920
[Guest]: while. And so I think I don't, yeah, you know, so let me put it this way. I was just looking at some

01:52:08.920 --> 01:52:16.520
[Guest]: data today. And the amount of work being demanded in the Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment

01:52:16.520 --> 01:52:25.000
[Guest]: Guarantee Scheme has just gone through the roof. Okay. In the first seven days of today's what,

01:52:25.000 --> 01:52:30.600
[Amit Varma]: 8th, right? Yeah, we are recording on June 8th, and this episode will be out on June 4th. Right.

01:52:30.600 --> 01:52:38.120
[Guest]: So today is 8th. So in the first eight days of the month, the 2.12 crore households have demanded

01:52:38.120 --> 01:52:45.480
[Guest]: work under NREGA. Okay. Whereas last year, the number for the full month of June was around 2.56

01:52:45.480 --> 01:52:51.400
[Guest]: crore. So that tells you the amount of work that is being demanded. Now, just because you're

01:52:51.400 --> 01:52:58.840
[Guest]: demanding work doesn't mean that you'll get it. The other thing is that agriculture in India

01:52:58.840 --> 01:53:03.400
[Guest]: already has a huge amount of disguised unemployment, which basically means that it

01:53:03.400 --> 01:53:09.720
[Guest]: has many more people than is economically justifiable. So it contributes around 15 to 16%

01:53:10.680 --> 01:53:17.880
[Guest]: of the Indian economy and employs more than 40% of India's workforce. Now, imagine all these people

01:53:17.880 --> 01:53:24.920
[Guest]: going back and, you know, becoming either a part of the agriculture workforce or demanding work

01:53:24.920 --> 01:53:30.360
[Guest]: under NREGA. I mean, what do they do there to continue earning a living? Now, one reason that

01:53:30.360 --> 01:53:36.360
[Guest]: they came to, you know, the cities from, you know, from the places where they originally belonged to

01:53:36.360 --> 01:53:42.840
[Guest]: was looking for work. And they came because there was no work where they came from. Right. And

01:53:42.840 --> 01:53:48.280
[Guest]: suddenly when they're going back, I mean, how are they going to get work there? I mean,

01:53:48.280 --> 01:53:55.080
[Guest]: I can understand that, you know, the government can increase allocation towards NREGA and create

01:53:55.080 --> 01:54:00.120
[Guest]: some work. But then that's one, it's very low-end work and two, it doesn't pay much.

01:54:01.000 --> 01:54:08.520
[Guest]: So ultimately, I don't know. I mean, I think the people who have gone back may have, you know,

01:54:08.520 --> 01:54:17.800
[Guest]: no other way but to come back to the cities and hope that they sort of get the jobs that they

01:54:17.800 --> 01:54:24.280
[Guest]: originally had. I mean, I can't see any other way out. I mean, I have thought about this over and

01:54:24.280 --> 01:54:31.960
[Guest]: over again. And I don't, I mean, unless the chief ministers of Bihar and UP and Jharkhand and even

01:54:31.960 --> 01:54:39.080
[Guest]: Odisha and Chhattisgarh to some extent end up creating a lot of work within the state. I mean,

01:54:39.080 --> 01:54:44.200
[Guest]: in that ecosystem, even if it happens, it's not going to come up in two years or three years or

01:54:44.200 --> 01:54:49.880
[Guest]: five years. And I mean, one is you don't see any commitment from any of the leaders in that

01:54:49.880 --> 01:54:54.920
[Guest]: direction. And two is even if there is a commitment, it's not, you know, Bangalore wasn't built in a

01:54:54.920 --> 01:55:02.200
[Guest]: day, right? I mean, it took the city close to 20 years to reach where it did. I mean, and I'm not

01:55:02.200 --> 01:55:07.800
[Guest]: talking about the Bangalore traffic here. But the fact of the matter is that there are, you know,

01:55:07.800 --> 01:55:13.480
[Guest]: it is a city, there are a lot of IT companies based out of it. And there is a lot of work being

01:55:13.480 --> 01:55:18.520
[Guest]: created in that city all said and done. So I don't know, I don't think I mean, I have come around to

01:55:18.520 --> 01:55:25.080
[Guest]: the conclusion that these people will have to, for whatever be the case, will have to come back.

01:55:25.800 --> 01:55:31.640
[Guest]: And I just hope that, you know, this time around, they get treated much better. I mean,

01:55:31.640 --> 01:55:37.640
[Guest]: there have been some very good stories on how people, you know, employers in the southern states

01:55:37.640 --> 01:55:42.680
[Guest]: are giving AC tickets to some of their employees to come back. Some of them have even been flown in.

01:55:42.680 --> 01:55:48.120
[Guest]: I just hope that this goodwill or whatever you might call it, this just lasts for a while. And

01:55:48.120 --> 01:55:53.080
[Guest]: I don't know, I mean, otherwise, I don't see how they can, you know, make a living in these states.

01:55:53.080 --> 01:55:59.000
[Guest]: You know, one is that, you know, if you look at places like Bihar, the size of the agriculture

01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:04.600
[Guest]: plot is already very small and average agriculture plot, not, I mean, and that being the case,

01:56:04.600 --> 01:56:09.400
[Guest]: how do you make a living out of being a farmer? I mean, the reason that you moved out of that

01:56:09.400 --> 01:56:14.280
[Guest]: place was because you couldn't make, continue making living as a farmer. So, which is again,

01:56:14.280 --> 01:56:19.560
[Guest]: you know, I'd like to connect this to the point that, which is why it is very important to get

01:56:19.560 --> 01:56:25.000
[Guest]: the construction and the real estate sector going all over again, because, which is where, I mean,

01:56:25.000 --> 01:56:31.000
[Guest]: which can sort of, again, you know, create jobs in smaller cities where people can then, you know,

01:56:31.000 --> 01:56:37.720
[Guest]: sort of hope to work at least, if not in the village, but at least in the city that is nearest

01:56:37.720 --> 01:56:42.040
[Amit Varma]: to wherever they live. Yeah, so two thoughts strike me here. One is, of course, like you said,

01:56:42.040 --> 01:56:46.680
[Amit Varma]: it's a great opportunity for those states. Now that they have all those people back there to

01:56:46.680 --> 01:56:51.960
[Amit Varma]: do something about it, because I continue to maintain that every human being is, you know,

01:56:51.960 --> 01:56:56.760
[Amit Varma]: add something to the world, they are not a burden on it. And it's a great opportunity for them to

01:56:56.760 --> 01:57:01.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of revamp the regulatory system and sort of but like you said, it won't happen overnight.

01:57:01.880 --> 01:57:05.960
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, what do we do now? And I can't really see a way out. What I'd also like to sort

01:57:05.960 --> 01:57:10.840
[Amit Varma]: of tell my listeners is that I've done a bunch of episodes on agriculture, which I rather like a lot

01:57:10.840 --> 01:57:16.600
[Guest]: and I shall link them from the show notes. You should definitely link the one that you did with

01:57:16.600 --> 01:57:22.280
[Guest]: Shetkari. You should definitely link that one. That's I think the best of the lot.

01:57:22.280 --> 01:57:27.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's a wonderful episode, episode 86. The only episode I've done in Hindi, by the way.

01:57:27.080 --> 01:57:30.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so moving on. I mean, we're kind of approaching the end of the episode. And in a

01:57:30.520 --> 01:57:36.600
[Amit Varma]: sense, we are also kind of approaching the end of the lockdown. And recently, you wrote a piece

01:57:36.600 --> 01:57:42.840
[Amit Varma]: talking about how the end of the lockdown will not bring life back to normal. Can I ask you to

01:57:43.400 --> 01:57:45.400
[Amit Varma]: sort of elaborate a bit on this?

01:57:45.400 --> 01:57:50.120
[Guest]: Huh? I mean, see, in the sense that, you know, people are still apprehensive of, you know,

01:57:50.120 --> 01:57:55.880
[Guest]: going out and spending money. You know, you have parts of the transport system, which are working

01:57:55.880 --> 01:58:02.280
[Guest]: parts, which are not. So I don't know. I mean, you know, if you open it up too much, obviously,

01:58:02.280 --> 01:58:09.240
[Guest]: there is, you know, the risk of COVID-19 spreading more than it already is. If you don't open it up,

01:58:09.240 --> 01:58:14.040
[Guest]: then there is the problem of, you know, economic activity not really picking up. So how do you,

01:58:15.000 --> 01:58:21.320
[Guest]: I don't know. I mean, I don't think there is a balance to this. And our health system isn't

01:58:21.320 --> 01:58:28.680
[Guest]: really, you know, it just can't really cope up with the, you know, if any more increases in the

01:58:28.680 --> 01:58:35.160
[Guest]: disease happen in the days to come. And in fact, in Mumbai, the medical system is on the verge of

01:58:35.160 --> 01:58:39.880
[Guest]: collapse. And it's not that there are no, I mean, there are enough beds, it's just that there aren't

01:58:39.880 --> 01:58:45.240
[Guest]: enough nurses and ward boys, which is very, very, you know, which is why again, it is you need

01:58:45.240 --> 01:58:51.640
[Guest]: everyone to sort of be there for a system to work and which is really not happening. So.

01:58:51.640 --> 01:58:56.120
[Amit Varma]: That's incredibly bleak. I think we've taken up enough of the listeners time this week,

01:58:56.120 --> 01:59:01.160
[Amit Varma]: but no worry, we shall come at you every week in our new show Econ Central. And we will also

01:59:01.160 --> 01:59:06.520
[Amit Varma]: discuss on episode one of that which will come this Thursday, a topic which we haven't found

01:59:06.520 --> 01:59:12.600
[Amit Varma]: time for in this episode, which is this whole, you know, tirade against China, boycott China,

01:59:12.600 --> 01:59:17.320
[Amit Varma]: return to Nehru's import substitution under different names and a rhetoric spread on a

01:59:17.320 --> 01:59:22.760
[Amit Varma]: different kind of media entirely. What would Nehru have thought of WhatsApp, I wonder. So,

01:59:22.760 --> 01:59:28.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, do sort of check that show out our website is econcentral.in. You can go to all

01:59:28.920 --> 01:59:34.920
[Amit Varma]: your podcast apps right now and search for Econ Central. I hope the, you know, the RSS feed has

01:59:34.920 --> 01:59:39.000
[Amit Varma]: spread widely enough and you'll be able to see the preview episode.

01:59:39.000 --> 01:59:40.680
[Guest]: Can I make another poor joke here?

01:59:40.680 --> 01:59:42.120
[Guest]: Kindly do, kindly.

01:59:42.120 --> 01:59:47.400
[Guest]: So, you know, I don't know what RSS feeds, but RSS is definitely widely spread.

01:59:49.560 --> 01:59:55.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you could. Yeah, indeed. So we won't comment, we won't make a value judgment on that.

01:59:55.880 --> 02:00:01.160
[Amit Varma]: It's an indisputable fact. And so Vivek, you know, thank you so much for coming on the show.

